1103/PhysRevLett.83.4963}}\n* S. G. Lukishova, L. J. Bissell, J. Winkler, and C. R. Stroud, Jr., ''Resonance in quantum dot fluorescence in a photonic bandgap liquid crystal host'', Optics Letters 37, 1259-1261 (2012). {{DOI|10.1364/OL.37.001259}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hajim.rochester.edu/optics/people/faculty/stroud_carlos/index.html Homepage of Carlos Stroud] at the University of Rochester (Hajim School of Engineering & Applied Sciences)\n*[https://www.pas.rochester.edu/people/faculty/stroud_carlos/index.html Homepage of Carlos Stroud] at the University of Rochester (Department of Physics and Astronomy)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stroud, Carlos Ray Jr.}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:Washington University physicists]]\n[[Category:University of Rochester faculty]]\n[[Category:Optical physicists]]\n[[Category:Quantum physicists]]\n[[Category:People from Owensboro, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Centre College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Stroud"}
{"title_page": "Phoenician language", "text_new": "{{Contains special characters\n| special    = Phoenician characters\n| fix        = Help:Multilingual support\n| error      = [[Specials (Unicode block)#Replacement character|question marks, empty boxes, or other symbols]]\n| characters = the intended characters\n| image      = Phoenician mem.svg\n| alt        = Phoenician character mem\n| link       = Specials (Unicode block)#Replacement character\n| section    = article\n| compact    = \n}}\n{{Infobox language\n| name = Phoenician\n| nativename = \n| states = [[Canaan]]; later spoken in coastal outposts and islands throughout the Mediterranean.\n| script = [[Phoenician alphabet]]\n| era = attested in Phoenicia proper from the 11th century BCE to the 2nd century CE<ref>Holmstedt, Robert (2017), \"Phoenician\" in ''A Companion to Ancient Phoenicia'', London: Wiley-Blackwell, p. 1</ref>\n| familycolor = Afro-Asiatic\n| fam2 = [[Semitic languages|Semitic]]\n| fam3 = [[West Semitic languages|West Semitic]]\n| fam4 = [[Central Semitic languages|Central Semitic]]\n| fam5 = [[Northwest Semitic languages|Northwest Semitic]]\n| fam6 = [[Canaanite languages|Canaanite]]\n| iso1 = \n| iso2 = phn\n| iso3 = phn\n| map = File:Phoenician Language.png\n| mapcaption = Distribution of the Phoenician language\n| glotto = phoe1239\n| glottoname = Phoenician\n| glotto2 = phoe1238\n| glottoname2 = Phoenician\u2013Punic\n| notice = IPA\n}}\n{{SpecialChars|fix=Help:Special characters#Phoenician}}\n'''Phoenician''' was a language originally spoken in the coastal (Mediterranean) region, then called \"''P\u016bt''\" (in Phoenician and [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]]), \"[[Canaan]]\" (in [[Biblical Hebrew]], [[Old Arabic]], and [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]]), and \"[[Phoenicia]]\" (in [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Latin]]). It is a part of the [[Canaanite languages|Canaanite subgroup]] of the [[Northwest Semitic languages]]. Other members of the family are [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Ammonite language|Ammonite]], [[Moabite language|Moabite]], and [[Edomite language|Edomite]].<ref name=\"Glenn Markoe p108\">Glenn Markoe.''Phoenicians''. p. 108. University of California Press, 2000.</ref><ref name=\"Zellig Sabbettai Harris p6\">Zellig Sabbettai Harris. ''A grammar of the Phoenician language''. p. 6. 1990.</ref>\n\nThe area in which Phoenician was spoken includes [[Syria (region)|Greater Syria]] and, at least as a prestige language, [[Anatolia]], specifically the areas now including [[Lebanon]], coastal [[Syria]], coastal northern [[Israel]], parts of [[Cyprus]] and some adjacent areas of [[Turkey]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SLSzNfdcqfoC|last=Lipi\u0144ski|first=Edward|year=2004|title=Itineraria Phoenicia|pages=139\u201341|isbn=9789042913448}}</ref> It was also spoken in the area of [[Phoenician colonies|Phoenician colonization]] along the coasts of the southwestern [[Mediterranean Sea]], including those of modern [[Tunisia]], [[Morocco]], [[Libya]] and [[Algeria]] as well as [[Malta]], the west of [[Sicily]], [[Sardinia]], [[Corsica]], the [[Balearic Islands]] and southernmost [[Spain]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Phoenicia]]ns were the first state-level society to make extensive use of the [[History of the alphabet#Semitic alphabet|Semitic alphabet]]. The [[Phoenician alphabet]] is the oldest verified [[consonant]]al alphabet, or ''[[abjad]].''<ref>{{cite book|last=Fischer|first=Steven Roger|title=A history of writing|publisher=Reaktion Books|year=2004|page=90}}</ref> It has become conventional to refer to the script as \"Proto-Canaanite\" until the mid-11th century BC, when it is first attested on inscribed [[bronze]] arrowheads, and as \"Phoenician\" only after 1050 BC.<ref>Markoe, Glenn E.,  ''Phoenicians''. University of California Press. {{ISBN|0-520-22613-5}} (2000) (hardback) p. 111.</ref> The Phoenician phonetic alphabet is generally believed to be at least the partial ancestor of almost all modern alphabets.\n[[File:Phoenician trade routes (eng).svg|thumb|350px|The most important Phoenician trade routes and cities in the [[Mediterranean Basin]]]]\nFrom a traditional linguistic perspective, Phoenician was composed of a variety of dialects.<ref name=\"Glenn Markoe p108\"/><ref name=\"Zellig Sabbettai Harris p6\"/> However, the very slight differences in language and the insufficient records of the time make it unclear whether Phoenician formed a separate and united dialect or was merely a superficially defined part of a broader [[language continuum]]. Through their maritime trade, the Phoenicians spread the use of the alphabet to Northwest Africa and Europe, where it was adopted by the [[Ancient Greece|Greeks]]. Later, the [[Etruscan civilization|Etruscans]] adopted a modified version for their own use, which, in turn, was modified and adopted by the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] and became the Latin alphabet.<ref>Edward Clodd, ''Story of the Alphabet'' (Kessinger) 2003:192ff</ref>\n\nPunic colonisation spread Phoenician to the western Mediterranean, where the distinct [[Punic language]] developed. Punic also died out, but it seems to have survived far longer than Phoenician, perhaps into the 9th century AD.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=M8oNAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA50|title=Report on the Ph\u0153nician and Roman Antiquities in the Group of the Islands of Malta|last=Caruana|first=A. A.|date=1852|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|isbn=|location=|pages=50|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Writing system==\n{{main|Phoenician alphabet}}\nPhoenician was written with the Phoenician script, an [[abjad]] (consonantary) originating from the [[Proto-Canaanite alphabet]] that also became the basis for the [[Greek alphabet]] and, via an Etruscan adaptation, the [[Latin alphabet]]. The Punic form of the script gradually developed somewhat different and more cursive letter shapes; in the 3rd century BC, it also began to exhibit a tendency to mark the presence of vowels, especially final vowels, with an [[aleph]] or sometimes an [[ayin]]. Furthermore, around the time of the [[Second Punic War]], an even more cursive form began to develop,<ref>Jongeling, K. and Robert Kerr. Late Punic epigraphy. P.10.</ref> which gave rise to a variety referred to as Neo-Punic and existed alongside the more conservative form and became predominant some time after the [[Battle of Carthage (c. 149 BC)|destruction of Carthage (c. 149 BC)]].<ref name=benz>Benz, Franz L. 1982. Personal Names in the Phoenician and Punic Inscriptions. P.12-14</ref> Neo-Punic, in turn, tended to designate vowels with [[mater lectionis|matres lectionis]] (\"consonantal letters\") more frequently than the previous systems had and also began to systematically use different letters for different vowels,<ref name=benz/> in the way explained in more detail below. Finally, a number of late inscriptions from what is now [[Constantine, Algeria]] dated to the first century BC make use of the Greek alphabet to write Punic, and many inscriptions from [[Tripolitania]], in the third and fourth centuries AD use the Latin alphabet for that purpose.<ref>Jongeling, K. and Robert Kerr. Late Punic epigraphy. P.2.</ref>\n\nIn Phoenician writing, unlike that of abjads such as those of Aramaic, Biblical Hebrew and Arabic, even long vowels remained generally unexpressed, regardless of their origin (even if they originated from diphthongs, as in '''bt''' {{IPA|/be\u02d0t/}} 'house'; Hebrew spelling has '''byt'''). Eventually, Punic writers began to implement systems of marking of vowels by means of ''matres lectionis''. In the 3rd century BC appeared the practice of using final [[aleph|'\u0101lep]] [[File:phoenician aleph.svg|10px]] to mark the presence of any final vowel and, occasionally, of [[yodh|y\u014dd]] [[File:Phoenician_yodh.svg|10px]] to mark a final long {{IPA|[i\u02d0]}}.\n\nLater, mostly after the destruction of Carthage in the so-called \"Neo-Punic\" inscriptions, that was supplemented by a system in which [[Waw (letter)|w\u0101w]] [[File:Phoenician waw.svg|10px]] denoted {{IPA|[u]}}, y\u014dd [[File:Phoenician_yodh.svg|10px]] denoted {{IPA|[i]}}, '\u0101lep [[File:phoenician aleph.svg|10px]] denoted {{IPA|[e]}} and {{IPA|[o]}}, [[ayin|\u02bfayin]] [[File:Phoenician_ayin.svg|10px]] denoted {{IPA|[a]}}{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=85}} and [[he (letter)|h\u0113]] [[File:Phoenician_he.svg|10px]] and [[Heth|{{transl|sem|\u1e25\u0113t}}]] [[File:phoenician heth.png|10px]] could also be used to signify {{IPA|[a]}}.<ref>Jongeling, K., Robert M. Kerr. 2005. Late Punic epigraphy: an introduction to the study of Neo-Punic and Latino-Punic Inscriptions</ref> This latter system was used first with foreign words and was then extended to many native words as well.\n\nA third practice reported in the literature is the use of the consonantal letters for vowels in the same way as had occurred in the original adaptation of the Phoenician alphabet to Greek and Latin, which was apparently still transparent to Punic writers: h\u0113 [[File:Phoenician_he.svg|10px]] for {{IPA|[e]}} and '\u0101lep [[File:phoenician aleph.svg|10px]] for {{IPA|[a]}}.{{sfn|Segert|1997|p=175}}\n\nLater, Punic inscriptions began to be written in the Latin alphabet, which also indicated the vowels. Those later inscriptions, in addition with some inscriptions in Greek letters and transcriptions of Phoenician names into other languages, represent the main source of knowledge about Phoenician vowels.\n\n==Phonology==\n\n===Consonants===\nThe Phoenician orthography (see ''[[Phoenician alphabet]]'') distinguishes the following consonants<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Phoenician Punic grammar|last=Krahmalkov, Charles R.|date=2001|publisher=Brill|isbn=9004117717|location=|pages=20\u201327|oclc=237631007}}</ref> (the standard transliteration of the corresponding Phoenician graphemes is marked in '''bold'''):<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DbC9CwAAQBAJ&lpg=PR1&dq=krahmalkov%20phoenician&pg=PA132#v=onepage&q=for%20his%20son&f=false|title=A Phoenician-Punic Grammar|last=Krahmalkov|first=Charles R.|date=2000-11-28|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004294202|location=|pages=21|language=en}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" id=\"ipa_table\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Labial\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Dental\n! colspan=\"2\" |Alveolar\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Palatal\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Velar\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Uvular\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Pharyngeal\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Glottal\n|-\n!<small>Plain</small>\n!<small>Emphatic</small>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Nasal\n|{{IPA|m}} '''m'''\n|\n|{{IPA|n}} '''n'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Stop\n!<small>Voiceless</small>\n|{{IPA|p}} '''p'''\n|\n|{{IPA|t}} '''\u1e6d''' \n|\n|\n|{{IPA|k}} '''k'''\n|{{IPA|q}} '''q'''\n|\n|{{IPA|\u0294}} \u02be\n|-\n!<small>Voiced</small>\n|{{IPA|b}} '''b'''\n|\n|{{IPA|d}} '''d'''\n|\n|\n|{{IPA|\u0261}} '''g'''\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Affricate\n!<small>Voiceless</small>\n|\n|\n|{{IPA|t\u0361s}} '''\u1e63'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!<small>Voiced</small>\n|\n|\n|{{IPA|d\u0361z}} '''z'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Fricative\n!<small>Voiceless</small>\n|\n|{{IPA|\u03b8}} '''t'''\n|{{IPA|s}} '''s'''\n|\n|{{IPA|\u0283}} '''\u0161'''\n|{{IPA|x}} '''\u1e25'''\n|\n|\n|{{IPA|h}} '''h'''\n|-\n!<small>Voiced</small>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|{{IPA|\u0295}} \u02bf\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Trill\n|\n|\n|{{IPA|r}} '''r'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Approximant\n|\n|\n|{{IPA|l}} '''l'''\n|\n|{{IPA|j}} '''y'''\n|{{IPA|w}} '''w'''\n|\n|\n|\n|}\nThe system reflected in the abjad above is the product of several mergers. From Proto-Northwest Semitic to Canaanite, {{transl|sem|*\u0161}} and {{transl|sem|*\u1e6f }} have merged into {{transl|sem|*\u0161}}, {{transl|sem|*\u1e0f}} and {{transl|sem|*z}} have merged into {{transl|sem|*z}}, and {{transl|sem|*\u1e71}}, {{transl|sem|*\u1e63\u0301}} and {{transl|sem|*\u1e63}} have merged into * \u1e63. Next, from Canaanite to Phoenician, the sibilants {{transl|sem|*\u015b}} and {{transl|sem|*\u0161}} were merged as {{transl|sem|*\u0161}}, {{transl|sem|*\u1e2b}} and {{transl|sem|*\u1e25}} were merged as {{transl|sem|\u1e25}}, and *{{transl|sem|\u02bb}} and *{{transl|sem|\u0121}} were merged as *{{transl|sem|\u02bb}}.{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=87}}<ref name=\":0\" />{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} These latter developments also occurred in Biblical Hebrew at one point or another.\n\n==== Sibilants ====\nThe original value of the [[Proto-Semitic language|Proto-Semitic]] sibilants, and accordingly of their Phoenician counterparts, is disputed. Recent scholarship argues that {{transl|sem|\u0161}} was {{IPA|[s]}}, {{transl|sem|s}} was {{IPA|[ts]}}, {{transl|sem|z}} was {{IPA|[dz]}}, and {{transl|sem|\u1e63}} was {{IPA|[ts\u02bc]}},{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=86}} against the traditional sound values of {{IPA|[\u0283]}}, {{IPA|[s]}}, {{IPA|[z]}}, and {{IPA|[s\u02e4]}} as reflected in the transcription.{{sfn|Segert|1997|p=59}}\n\nOn the other hand, it is debated whether [[shin (letter)|\u0161\u012bn]] [[File:Phoenician_sin.svg|10px]] and [[samekh|s\u0101mek]] [[File:Phoenician_samekh.svg|10px]], which are mostly well distinguished by the Phoenician orthography, also eventually merged at some point, either in Classical Phoenician or in Late Punic.<ref>Kerr, Robert M. 2010. Latino-Punic Epigraphy: A Descriptive Study of the Inscriptions. P.126</ref> Krahmalkov suggests that *z may have been [dz] or even [zd] based on Latin transcriptions such as ''esde'' for the demonstrative {{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd05}} ''z.''<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Postvelars ====\nIn later Punic, the laryngeals and pharyngeals seem to have been entirely lost. Neither these nor the emphatics could be adequately represented by the Latin alphabet, but there is also evidence to that effect from Punic script transcriptions.\n\n==== Lenition ====\nThere is no consensus on whether Phoenician-Punic ever underwent the [[lenition]] of [[stop consonant]]s that happened in most other Northwest Semitic languages such as Biblical Hebrew and Aramaic (cf. Hackett{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=87}} vs Segert{{sfn|Segert|1997}} and Lyavdansky).<ref name=\"lyavd\" /> The consonant {{IPA|/p/}} may have been ''generally'' transformed into {{IPA|/f/}} in Punic and in late Phoenician, as it was in Proto-Arabic.<ref name=\"lyavd\">\u041b\u044f\u0432\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439, \u0410.\u041a. 2009. \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a. \u042f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430: \u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438. \u0410\u043a\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a. \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0437\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438. \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u0411\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u0410.\u0413. \u0438 \u0434\u0440. P.283</ref> Certainly, Latin-script renditions of late Punic include many spirantized transcriptions with ''ph'', ''th'' and ''kh'' in various positions (although the interpretation of these spellings is not entirely clear) as well as the letter ''f'' for the original *p.<ref>Kerr, Robert M. 2010 Latino-Punic Epigraphy: A Descriptive Study of the Inscriptions. P.105 ff.</ref> However, in Neo-Punic, *b lenited to v contiguous to a following consonant, as in the Latin transcription ''lifnim'' for {{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd0b\ud802\udd01\ud802\udd0d\ud802\udd0c}} *lbnm \"for his son\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Vowels===\nKnowledge of the vowel system is very imperfect because of the characteristics of the writing system. During most of its existence, Phoenician writing showed no vowels at all, and even as vowel notation systems did eventually arise late in its history, they never came to be applied consistently to native vocabulary. It is thought that Phoenician had the short vowels {{IPA|/a/}}, {{IPA|/i/}}, {{IPA|/u/}} and the long vowels {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}}, {{IPA|/i\u02d0/}}, {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}}, {{IPA|/e\u02d0/}}, {{IPA|/o\u02d0/}}.{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=87}}{{sfn|Segert|1997|p=60}} The Proto-Semitic diphthongs {{IPA|/aj/}} and {{IPA|/aw/}} are realized as {{IPA|/e\u02d0/}} and {{IPA|/o\u02d0/}}. That must have happened earlier than in Biblical Hebrew since the resultant long vowels are not marked with the semivowel letters (''b\u0113t'' \"house\" was written {{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd01\ud802\udd15}} '''bt''', in contrast to Biblical Hebrew {{Hebrew|\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea}} '''byt''').\n\nThe most conspicuous vocalic development in Phoenician is the so-called [[Canaanite shift]], partly shared by Biblical Hebrew, but going further in Phoenician. The Proto-Northwest Semitic {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} and {{IPA|/aw/}} became not merely {{IPA|/o\u02d0/}} as in [[Tiberian Hebrew]], but {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}}. Stressed Proto-Semitic {{IPA|/a/}} became Tiberian Hebrew {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}} ({{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} in other traditions), but Phoenician {{IPA|/o\u02d0/}}. The shift is proved by Latin and Greek transcriptions like ''r\u016bs'' for \"head, cape\" (Tiberian Hebrew ''r\u014d\u0161'', {{Hebrew|\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9}}), ''sam\u014d'' for \"he heard\" (Tiberian Hebrew ''\u0161\u0101m\u0101\u02bb'', {{Hebrew|\u05e9\u05de\u05e2}}); similarly the word for \"eternity\" is known from Greek transcriptions to have been ''\u02bb\u016bl\u014dm'', corresponding to Biblical Hebrew ''\u02bb\u014dl\u0101m'' and Proto-Semitic ''\u02bb\u0101lam''. The letter Y used for words such as ''ys'' \"which\" and ''yth'' (definite accusative marker) in Greek and Latin alphabet inscriptions can be interpreted as denoting a reduced [[schwa]] vowel{{sfn|Segert|1997|p=175}} that occurred in pre-stress syllables in verbs and two syllables before stress in nouns and adjectives,{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=88}} while other instances of Y as in ''chyl'' and even ''chil'' for /kull/ \"all\" in ''[[Poenulus]]'' can be interpreted as a further stage in the vowel shift resulting in fronting ({{IPA|[y]}}) and even subsequent delabialization of {{IPA|/u/}} and {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}}.{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=88}}{{sfn|Segert|1997|p=61}} Short {{IPA|/*i/}} in originally-open syllables was lowered to {{IPA|[e]}} and was also lengthened if it was accented.{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=88}}\n\n===Suprasegmentals===\n\nStress-dependent vowel changes indicate that stress was probably mostly final, as in Biblical Hebrew.{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=89}} Long vowels probably occurred only in open syllables.{{sfn|Segert|1997|p=63}}\n\n==Grammar==\nAs is typical for the Semitic languages, Phoenician words are usually built around consonantal roots and vowel changes are used extensively to express [[Morphology (linguistics)|morphological]] distinctions. However, unlike most Semitic languages, Phoenician preserved numerous uniconsonantal and biconsonantal roots inherited from [[Proto-Afroasiatic language|Proto-Afro-Asiatic]]: compare the verbs '''kn''' \"to be\" vs Arabic '''kwn''', '''mt''' \"to die\" vs Hebrew and Arabic '''mwt''' and '''sr''' \"to remove\" vs Hebrew '''srr'''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=i08KAQAAMAAJ&q=|title=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr die alttestamentliche Wissenschaft|last=Stade|first=Bernhard|last2=Marti|first2=Karl|date=1970|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=|location=|pages=272|language=de}}</ref>\n\n===No<span class=\"ve-ce-branchNode-slug ve-ce-branchNode-inlineSlug\"></span>minal morphology===\nNouns are marked for gender (masculine and feminine), number (singular, plural and vestiges of the dual) and state (absolute and construct, the latter being nouns that are followed by their possessors) and also have the category definiteness. There is some evidence for remains of the Proto-Semitic genitive [[grammatical case]] as well. While many of the endings coalesce in the standard orthography, inscriptions in the Latin and Greek alphabet permit the reconstruction of the noun endings, which are also the adjective endings, as follows:<ref>Segert, Stanislav. 2007. Phoenician and Punic Morphology. In Morphologies of Asia and Philippines Morphologies of Asia and Africa. ed. by Alan S. Kaye. P.79</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n!\n!Singular\n!Dual\n!Plural\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Masculine\n|Absolute\n|'''\u2205'''\n|{{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd0c}} '''m''' /-\u0113m/\n|{{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd0c}} '''m''' /-\u012bm/\n|-\n|Construct\n|'''\u2205'''\n|'''\u2205''' /-\u0113/\n|'''\u2205''' /-\u0113/\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Feminine\n|Absolute\n|{{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd15}} '''t''' /-(a/i/o)t/\n|{{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd15\ud802\udd0c}} '''tm''' /-t\u0113m/\n|{{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd15}} '''t''' /-\u016bt/\n|-\n|Construct\n|{{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd15}} '''t''' /-(a/i/o)t/\n|{{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd15\ud802\udd0d}} '''tn''' /-t\u0113n/\n|{{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd15}} '''t''' /-\u016bt/\n|}\nIn late Punic, the final {{IPA|/-t/}} of the feminine was apparently dropped: {{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd07\ud802\udd0c\ud802\udd0b\ud802\udd0a\ud802\udd15}} '''{{transl|sem| \u1e25mlkt}}''' \"son of the queen\" or {{Script|Phnx|\ud802\udd00\ud802\udd07\ud802\udd0c\ud802\udd0b\ud802\udd0a\ud802\udd15}} '''{{transl|sem| \u02bc\u1e25mlkt}}''' \"brother of the queen\" rendered in Latin as HIMILCO.{{sfn|Segert|1997|p=61}}{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=90}} {{IPA|/n/}} was also assimilated to following consonants: e.g. {{transl|sem|'''\u0161t'''}} \"year\" for earlier {{transl|sem|*/sant/}}.{{sfn|Segert|1997|p=61}}\n\nThe case endings in general must have been lost between the 9th century BC and the 7th century BC:  the personal name rendered in [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] as '''ma-ti-nu-ba-{{transl|sem|\u02bc}}a-li''' \"Gift of [[Baal]]\", with the case endings '''-u''' and '''-i''', was written '''ma-ta-an-ba{{transl|sem|\u02bc}}a-al''' two centuries later. However, evidence has been found for a retention of the genitive case in the form of the first-singular possessive suffix: '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcby}}''' /{{transl|sem|\u02bc}}abiya/ \"of my father\" vs '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcb}}''' /{{transl|sem|\u02bc}}ab\u012b/ \"my father\". If true, this may suggest that cases were still distinguished to some degree in other forms as well.\n\nThe written forms and the reconstructed pronunciations of the personal pronouns are as follows:{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=85|loc=The description of the pronouns follows Hackett}}\n\nSingular: <br>\n1st: /{{transl|sem|\u02bcan\u014dk\u012b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcnk}}''' (Punic sometimes '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcnky}}'''), also attested as /{{transl|sem|\u02bcanek}}/<br>\n2nd masc. /{{transl|sem|\u02bcatta(\u02d0)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|\u02bct}}'''<br>\n2nd fem. /{{transl|sem|\u02bcatti(\u02d0)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|\u02bct}}'''<br>\n3rd masc. /{{transl|sem|hu\u02bc}}/ '''{{transl|sem|h\u02bc}}''', also [{{transl|sem|hy}}] (?) '''{{transl|sem|hy}}''' and /{{transl|sem|hu\u02bcat}}/ '''{{transl|sem|h\u02bct}}'''<br>\n3rd fem. /{{transl|sem|hi\u02bc}}/ '''{{transl|sem|h\u02bc}}'''\n\nPlural: <br>\n1st: /{{transl|sem|\u02bcana\u1e25n\u016b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcn\u1e25n}}''' <br>\n2nd masc. unattested<br>\n2nd fem. unattested<br>\n3rd masc. /{{transl|sem|hummat}}/ '''{{transl|sem|hmt}}''', <br>\n3rd fem. /{{transl|sem|himmat}}/ '''{{transl|sem|hmt}}'''\n\nEnclitic personal pronouns were added to nouns (to encode possession) and to prepositions, as shown below for \"Standard Phoenician\" (the predominant dialect, as distinct from the [[Byblos|Byblian]] and the late Punic varieties). They appear in a slightly different form depending on whether or not they follow plural-form masculine nouns (and so are added after a vowel). The former is given in brackets with the abbreviation a.V.\n\nSingular: <br>\n1st: /{{transl|sem|-\u012b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|\u2205}}''', also '''{{transl|sem|y}}''' (a.V. /{{transl|sem|-ayy}}/ '''{{transl|sem|y}}''') <br>\n2nd masc. /{{transl|sem|-ka(\u02d0)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|k}}'''<br>\n2nd fem. /{{transl|sem|-ki(\u02d0)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|k}}'''<br>\n3rd masc. /{{transl|sem|-o\u02d0}}/ '''{{transl|sem|\u2205}}''', Punic {{transl|sem|\u02bc}}, (a.V. /{{transl|sem|-\u0113yu(\u02d0)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|y}}''') <br>\n3rd fem. /{{transl|sem|-a\u02d0}}/ '''{{transl|sem|\u2205}}''', Punic {{transl|sem|\u02bc}} (a.V. /{{transl|sem|-\u0113ya(\u02d0)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|y}}''')\n\nPlural: <br>\n1st: /{{transl|sem|-o(\u02d0)n}}/ '''{{transl|sem|n}}'''<br>\n2nd masc. unattested<br>\n2nd fem. unattested<br>\n3rd masc. /{{transl|sem|-o(\u02d0)m}}/ '''{{transl|sem|m}}''' (a.V. /{{transl|sem|-n\u014dm}}/ '''{{transl|sem|nm}}''') <br>\n3rd fem. /{{transl|sem|-e(\u02d0)m}}/ '''{{transl|sem|m}}''' (a.V. /{{transl|sem|-n\u0113m}}/ '''{{transl|sem|nm}}''')\n\nIn addition, according to some research, the same written forms of the enclitics that are attested after vowels are also found after a singular noun in what must have been the genitive case (which ended in {{IPA|/-i/}}, whereas the plural version ended in {{IPA|/-\u0113/}}). Their pronunciation can then be reconstructed somewhat differently: first-person singular /{{transl|sem|-iya(\u02d0)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|y}}''', third-person singular masculine and feminine /{{transl|sem|-iyu(\u02d0)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|y}}''' and /{{transl|sem|-iya(\u02d0)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|y}}'''. The third-person plural singular and feminine must have pronounced the same in both cases, i.e. /{{transl|sem|-n\u014dm}}/ '''{{transl|sem|nm}}''' and /{{transl|sem|-n\u0113m}}/ '''{{transl|sem|nm}}'''.\n\nThese enclitic forms vary between the dialects. In the archaic [[Byblos|Byblian]] dialect, the third person forms are '''h''' and '''w''' /{{transl|sem|-\u014d}}/ for the masculine singular (a.V. '''w''' /{{transl|sem|-\u0113w}}/), '''h''' /{{transl|sem|-aha(\u02d0)}}/ for the feminine singular and '''hm''' /{{transl|sem|-hum(ma)}}/ for the masculine plural. In late Punic, the 3rd masculine singular is usually /{{transl|sem|-im}}/ '''{{transl|sem|m}}'''.\n\nThe same enclitic pronouns are also attached to verbs to denote direct objects. In that function, some of them have slightly divergent forms: first singular /{{transl|sem|-n\u012b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|n}}''' and probably first plural /{{transl|sem|-nu(\u02d0)}}/.\n\nThe near demonstrative pronouns (\"this\") are written, in standard Phoenician, '''z''' for the singular and '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcl}}''' for the plural. Cypriot Phoenician displays '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcz}}''' instead of '''z'''. Byblian still distinguishes, in the singular, a masculine '''{{transl|sem|zn}}''' / '''{{transl|sem|z}}''' from a feminine '''{{transl|sem|zt}}''' / '''{{transl|sem|z\u02bc}}'''. There are also many variations in Punic, including '''st''' and '''zt''' for both genders in the singular. The far demonstrative pronouns (\"that\") are identical to the independent third-person pronouns. The interrogative pronouns are {{IPA|/miya/}} or perhaps {{IPA|/mi/}} '''{{transl|sem|my}}''' \"who\" and {{IPA|/m\u016b/}} '''{{transl|sem|m}}''' \"what\". An indefinite pronoun \"anything\" is written '''mnm'''. The relative pronoun is a '''{{transl|sem|\u0161}}''', either followed or preceded by a vowel.\n\nThe definite article was {{IPA|/ha-/}}, and the first consonant of the following word was doubled. It was written '''h''' but in late Punic also '''{{transl|sem|\u02bc}}''' and '''{{transl|sem|\u02bb}}''' because of the weakening and coalescence of the gutturals. Much as in Biblical Hebrew, the initial consonant of the article is dropped after the prepositions '''b-''', '''l-''' and '''k'''; it could also be lost after various other particles and function words, such the direct object marker '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcyt}}''' and the conjunction '''w-''' \"and\".\n\nOf the cardinal numerals from 1 to 10, 1 is an adjective, 2 is formally a noun in the dual and the rest are nouns in the singular. They all distinguish gender: '''{{transl|sem|\u02bc\u1e25d}}''', '''{{transl|sem| \u0161nm/\u02bc\u0161nm}}'''<ref>Dictionary of the North-West Semitic Inscriptions: M-T Front Cover Jacob Hoftijzer, Karel Jongeling, Richard C. Steiner, Bezalel Porten, Adina Mosak Moshavi P.1176</ref> (construct state '''{{transl|sem|\u0161n/\u02bc\u0161n}}'''), '''{{transl|sem|\u0161l\u0161}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcrb\u02bb}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u1e25m\u0161}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u0161\u0161}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u0161b\u02bb}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u0161mn(h)}}''', '''{{transl|sem|t\u0161\u02bb}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u02bbsr/\u02bb\u0161r}}'''<ref>Ugaritische Grammatik, Josef Tropper P.73-80, {{ISBN|3927120901}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Die Keilalphabete: die ph\u00f6nizisch-kanaan\u00e4ischen und altarabischen Alphabete in Ugarit P.162, {{ISBN|3927120006}}</ref> vs '''{{transl|sem|\u02bc\u1e25t}}''', unattested, '''{{transl|sem|\u0161l\u0161t}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcrb\u02bbt}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u1e25m\u0161t}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u0161\u0161t}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u0161b\u02bbt}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u0161mnt}}''',<ref>P.994, http://www.persee.fr/doc/crai_0065-0536_2000_num_144_3_16174.</ref> unattested, '''{{transl|sem|\u02bb\u0161rt}}'''.<ref>Dictionary of the North-West Semitic Inscriptions: M-T Front Cover Jacob Hoftijzer, Karel Jongeling, Richard C. Steiner, Bezalel Porten, Adina Mosak Moshavi P.893</ref> The tens are morphologically masculine plurals of the ones: '''{{transl|sem|\u02bbsrm/\u02bb\u0161rm}}''',<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>Ph\u00f6nizisch-Punische Grammatik 3. Auflange P.171, {{ISBN|978-8876532597}}</ref> '''{{transl|sem|\u0161l\u0161m}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcrb\u02bbm}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u1e25m\u0161m}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u0161\u0161m}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u0161b\u02bbm}}''', '''{{transl|sem|\u0161mnm}}''', '''{{transl|sem|t\u0161\u02bbm}}'''. \"One hundred\" is '''{{transl|sem|m\u02bct}}''', two hundred is its dual form '''{{transl|sem|m\u02bctm}}''', whereas the rest are formed as in '''{{transl|sem|\u0161l\u0161 m\u02bct}}''' (three hundred). One thousand is '''{{transl|sem|\u02bclp}}'''. Ordinal numerals are formed by the addition of *iy '''{{transl|sem|-y}}'''.<ref>Segert, Stanislav. 2007. Phoenician and Punic Morphology. In Morphologies of Asia and Africa. Morphologies of Asia and Africa. ed. by Alan S. Kaye. P.80</ref> Composite numerals are formed with '''w-''' \"and\", e.g. '''{{transl|sem|\u02bbsr w \u0161nm }}''' for \"twelve\".\n\n===Verbal morphology===\nThe verb inflects for person, number, gender, tense and mood. Like for other Semitic languages, Phoenician verbs have different \"verbal patterns\" or \"stems\", expressing manner of action, level of transitivity and voice.\nThe perfect or suffix-conjugation, which expresses the past tense, is exemplified below with the root '''q-t-l''' \"to kill\" (a \"neutral\", G-stem).{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=90|loc=The vocalized reconstructions in the schemes below follow chiefly Hackett}}<ref>The spellings are based mostly on Segert, Stanislav. 2007. Phoenician and Punic Morphology. In Morphologies of Asia and Africa. Morphologies of Asia and Africa. ed. by Alan S. Kaye. P.82</ref>\n\nSingular: <br>\n1st: /{{transl|sem|qatalt\u012b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|qtlty}}'''<br>\n2nd masc. /{{transl|sem|qatalt\u0101}}/ '''{{transl|sem|qtlt}}'''<br>\n2nd fem. /{{transl|sem|qatalt(\u012b)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|qtlt}}'''<br>\n3rd masc. /{{transl|sem|qat\u014dl}}/ '''{{transl|sem|qtl}}'''<br>\n3rd fem. /{{transl|sem|qatal\u014d(t)}}/ '''{{transl|sem|qtlt}}''',<ref name=segert82>Segert, Stanislav. 2007. Phoenician and Punic Morphology. In Morphologies of Asia and Africa. Morphologies of Asia and Africa. ed. by Alan S. Kaye. P.82</ref> also '''{{transl|sem|qtl}}''', Punic '''{{transl|sem|qtl\u02bc}}'''\n\nPlural: <br>\n1st: /{{transl|sem|qataln\u016b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|qtln}}''' <br>\n2nd masc. unattested<br>\n2nd fem. unattested<br>\n3rd masc. {{transl|sem|qatal\u016b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|qtl}}''', Punic '''{{transl|sem|qtl\u02bc}}'''<br>\n3rd fem. unattested\n\nThe imperfect or prefix-conjugation, which expresses the present and future tense (and which is not distinguishable from the descendant of the Proto-Semitic [[jussive]] expressing wishes), is exemplified below, again with the root '''q-t-l'''.\n\n1st: /{{transl|sem|\u02bciqtul}}/ '''{{transl|sem|\u02bcqtl}}'''<br>\n2nd masc. /{{transl|sem|tiqtul}}/ '''{{transl|sem|tqtl}}'''<br>\n2nd fem. /{{transl|sem|tiqtul\u012b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|tqtly}}'''<br>\n3rd masc. /{{transl|sem|yiqtul}}/ '''{{transl|sem|yqtl}}'''<br>\n3rd fem. /{{transl|sem|tiqtul}}/ '''{{transl|sem|tqtl}}'''<br>\nPlural:\n1st: */{{transl|sem|niqtul}}/? '''{{transl|sem|*nqtl}}''' <br>\n2nd masc. /{{transl|sem|tiqtul\u016b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|*tqtl}}''', Punic '''{{transl|sem|*tqtl\u02bc}}'''<br>\n2nd fem. /{{transl|sem|tiqtulna}}/ '''{{transl|sem|tqtln}}'''<br>\n3rd masc. {{transl|sem|yiqtul\u016b}}/ '''{{transl|sem|yqtl}}'''<br>\n3rd fem. unattested\n\nThe imperative endings were presumably {{IPA|/-\u2205/}}, {{transl|sem|/-\u012b/}} and {{transl|sem|/-\u016b/}}<ref name=segert82/> for the second-person singular masculine, second-person singular feminine and second-person plural masculine respectively, but all three forms surface in the orthography as '''{{transl|sem|qtl}}''': '''{{transl|sem|-\u2205}}'''. The old Semitic jussive, which originally differed slightly from the prefix conjugation, is no longer possible to separate from it in Phoenician with the present data.\n\nThe non-finite forms are the infinitive construct, the infinitive absolute and the active and passive participles. In the G-stem, the infinitive construct is usually combined with the preposition '''l-''' \"to\", as in {{transl|sem|/liqtul/}} \"to kill\"; in contrast, the infinitive absolute (qat\u014dl){{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=96}} is mostly used to strengthen the meaning of a subsequent finite verb with the same root: {{transl|sem|'''pt\u1e25 tpt\u1e25 '''}} \"you will indeed open!\",<ref name=segert82/> accordingly /{{transl|sem|*qat\u014dl tiqtul}}/ \"you will indeed kill!\".\n\nThe participles had, in the G-stem, the following forms: <br>\nActive: <br>\nMasculine singular /{{transl|sem|q\u016btel}}/<ref name=segert82/> or /{{transl|sem|q\u014dtil}}/ {{transl|sem|'''qtl'''}}, plural /{{transl|sem|qotlim}}/<ref name=segert82/> or /{{transl|sem|q\u014dtil\u012bm}}/ {{transl|sem|'''qtl'''}}<br>\nFeminine singular {{transl|sem|'''qtlt'''}}, plural *{{transl|sem|'''qtlt'''}}<br>\nPassive: <br>\nMasculine singular /{{transl|sem|qat\u016bl}}/<ref name=segert82/> or /{{transl|sem|qat\u012bl}}/<ref name=lyavd293/> {{transl|sem|'''qtl'''}}, plural /{{transl|sem|qat\u016bl\u012bm}}/ {{transl|sem|'''qtlm'''}}<br>\nFeminine singular {{transl|sem|'''qtlt'''}}, plural /{{transl|sem|qat\u016bl\u014dt}}/ {{transl|sem|'''qtlt'''}}\n\nThe missing forms above can be inferred from the correspondences between the Proto-Northwest Semitic ancestral forms and the attested Phoenician counterparts: the PNWS participle forms are *{{transl|sem|/q\u0101til-, q\u0101til\u012bma, q\u0101til(a)t, q\u0101til\u0101t, qat\u016bl, qat\u016bl\u012bm, qatult or qat\u016blat, qat\u016bl\u0101t/}}.\n\nThe derived stems are:\n* the N-stem (functioning as a passive), e.g. '''nqtl''', the N-formant being lost in the prefix conjugation while assimilating and doubling the first root consonant ('''yqtl''').\n* the D-stem (functioning as a factitive): the forms must have been /qittil/ in the suffix conjugation, /yaqattil/ in the prefix conjugation, /qattil/ in the imperative and the infinitive construct, /qatt\u014dl/ in the infinitive absolute and /maqattil/ in the participle. The characteristic doubling of the middle consonant is only identifiable in foreign alphabet transcriptions.\n* the C-stem (functioning as a causative): the original *ha- prefix has produced *yi- rather than the Hebrew *hi-. The forms were apparently /yiqtil/ in the suffix conjugation ({{transl|sem|/\u02bciqtil}}/ in late Punic), /yaqtil/ in the prefix conjugation, and the infinitive is also /yaqtil/, while the participle was probably /maqtil/ or, in late Punic at least, /miqtil/.{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=97}}\n\nMost of the stems apparently also had passive and reflexive counterparts, the former differing through vowels, the latter also through the infix '''-t-'''. The G stem passive is attested as '''qytl''', {{transl|sem|/qytal/}} < *{{transl|sem|/qutal/}}.;<ref name=segert82/> t-stems can be reconstructed as /yitqatil/ '''ytqtl''' (tG) and /yiqtattil/ (Dt) '''yqttl'''.{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=99}}\n\n===Prepositions and particles===\nSome prepositions are always prefixed to nouns, deleting, if present, the initial {{IPA|/h/}} of the definite article: such are '''b-''' \"in\", '''l-''' \"to, for\", '''k-''' \"as\" and '''m-''' /{{transl|sem|min}}/ \"from\". They are sometimes found in forms extended through the addition of '''-n''' or '''-t'''. Other prepositions are not like that:{{transl|sem|'''\u02bbl'''}} \"upon\", .{{transl|sem|'''\u02bbd'''}} \"until\", {{transl|sem|'''\u02bc\u1e25r'''}} \"after\", {{transl|sem|'''t\u1e25t'''}} \"under\", {{transl|sem|'''b(y)n'''}} \"between\". New prepositions are formed with nouns: '''lpn''' \"in front of\", from '''l-''' \"to\" and '''pn''' \"face\". There is a special preposited marker of a definite object {{transl|sem|'''\u02bcyt'''}} (/{{transl|sem|\u02bciyy\u016bt}}/?), which, unlike Hebrew, is clearly distinct from the preposition {{transl|sem|'''\u02bct'''}} (/{{transl|sem|\u02bcitt}}/).\n\nThe most common negative marker is {{transl|sem|'''bl'''}} (/{{transl|sem|bal}}/), negating verbs but sometimes also nouns; another one is {{transl|sem|'''\u02bcy'''}} (/{{transl|sem|\u02bc\u012b}}/), expressing both nonexistence and the negation of verbs. Negative commands or prohibitions are expressed with {{transl|sem|'''\u02bcl'''}} (/{{transl|sem|\u02bcal}}/). \"Lest\" is {{transl|sem|'''lm'''}}. Some common conjunctions are {{transl|sem|'''w'''}} (originally perhaps /{{transl|sem|wa-?}}/, but certainly /{{transl|sem|u-}}/ in Late Punic), \"and\" {{transl|sem|'''\u02bcm'''}} ({{transl|sem|/\u02bcim/}}), \"when\", and {{transl|sem|'''k'''}} ({{transl|sem|/k\u012b/}}), \"that; because; when\". There was also a conjunction {{transl|sem|('''\u02bc''')'''p'''}} ({{transl|sem|/\u02bcap/}}\"also\". {{transl|sem|'''l-'''}} (/{{transl|sem|l\u016b, li}}/) could (rarely) be used to introduce desiderative constructions (\"may he do X!\"). {{transl|sem|'''l-'''}} could also introduce vocatives. Both prepositions and conjunctions could form compounds.{{sfn|Hackett|2008|p=98}}\n\n==Syntax==\nThe basic word order is [[verb-subject-object]]. There is no verb \"to be\" in the present tense; in clauses that would have used a copula, the subject may come before the predicate. Nouns precede their modifiers, such as adjectives and possessors.\n\n==Vocabulary and word formation==\nMost nouns are formed by a combination of consonantal roots and vocalic patterns, but they can formed also with prefixes ({{IPA|/m-/}}, expressing actions or their results, and rarely {{IPA|/t-/}}) and suffixes {{IPA|/-\u016bn/}}. Abstracts can be formed with the suffix '''-t''' (probably {{IPA|/-\u012bt/}}, {{IPA|/-\u016bt/}}).<ref name=lyavd293>\u041b\u044f\u0432\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439, \u0410.\u041a. 2009. \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a. \u042f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430: \u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438. \u0410\u043a\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a. \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0437\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438. \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u0411\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u0410.\u0413. \u0438 \u0434\u0440. P.293</ref> Adjectives can be formed following the familiar Semitic [[Arabic nouns and adjectives#Nisba|nisba]] suffix {{IPA|/-\u012by/}} '''y''' (e.g. '''\u1e63dny''' \"Sidonian\").\n\nLike the grammar, the vocabulary is very close to Biblical Hebrew, but some peculiarities attract attention. For example, the [[copula (linguistics)|copula]] verb \"to be\" is '''kn''' (as in Arabic, as opposed to Hebrew and Aramaic '''hyh''') and the verb \"to do\" is '''p\u02bfl''' (as in Aramaic '''p\u02bfl''' and Arabic '''f\u02bfl''', as opposed to Hebrew '''\u02bf\u015bh''', though in Hebrew '''p\u02bfl''' has the similar meaning \"to act\").\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"margin:auto\"\n|+Standard Phoenician<br />Sarcophagus inscription of Tabnit of Sidon, 5th century BC<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boothhouse.com/content/Booth_Using_Corpus_Linguistics.pdf |author=Booth, Scott W. |year=2007 |title=Using corpus linguistics to address some questiongs of Phoenician grammar and syntax found in the Kulamuwa inscription |page=196 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812194619/http://boothhouse.com/content/Booth_Using_Corpus_Linguistics.pdf |archivedate=August 12, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=proelal>{{cite web|url=http://www.proel.org/index.php?pagina=alfabetos/fenicio|title=Alfabeto fenicio|work=Proel (Promotora Espa\u00f1ola de Ling\u00fc\u00edstica)|access-date=5 July 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n! Text\n! Transliteration\n|- \n| align=right| {{script|Phnx|\ud802\udd00\ud802\udd0d\ud802\udd0a \ud802\udd15\ud802\udd01\ud802\udd0d\ud802\udd15 \ud802\udd0a\ud802\udd04\ud802\udd0d \ud802\udd0f\ud802\udd14\ud802\udd15\ud802\udd13\ud802\udd15 \ud802\udd0c\ud802\udd0b\ud802\udd0a \ud802\udd11\ud802\udd03\ud802\udd0d\ud802\udd0c \ud802\udd01\ud802\udd0d <br />  \ud802\udd00\ud802\udd14\ud802\udd0c\ud802\udd0d\ud802\udd0f\ud802\udd06\ud802\udd13 \ud802\udd0a\ud802\udd04\ud802\udd0d \ud802\udd0f\ud802\udd14\ud802\udd15\ud802\udd13\ud802\udd15 \ud802\udd0c\ud802\udd0b\ud802\udd0a \ud802\udd11\ud802\udd03\ud802\udd0d\ud802\udd0c \ud802\udd14\ud802\udd0a\ud802\udd01 \ud802\udd01\ud802