]], the son<br />of Eshmunazar, priest of Astarte, king of Sidon, am lying in this sarcophagus.<br />Whoever you are, any man that might find this sarcophagus,<br />don't, don't open it and don't disturb me,<br />for no silver is gathered with me, no gold is gathered with me, nor anything of value whatsoever,<br />only I am lying in this sarcophagus.<br />Don't, don't open it and don't disturb me,<br />for this thing is an abomination to Astarte.<br />And if you do indeed open it and do indeed disturb me,<br />may you not have any seed among the living under the sun,<br />nor a resting-place with the [[Rephaite]]s.\n|}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"margin:auto\"\n|+Late Punic<br /> 1st century BC<ref name=diako>{{cite book|author=\u0414\u044c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0418. \u041c|title=\u042f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 \u0434\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0435\u0439 \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u0437\u0438\u0438|publisher=\u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0430|location=\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430|year=1967}}</ref>\n! Text\n! Reconstruction (by [[Igor Diakonov]])<ref name=diako/>\n|- \n| align=right| \u039b\u0391\u0394\u039f\u03a5\u039d \u039b\u03a5\u0392\u0391\u039b \u0391\u039c\u039f\u03a5\u039d <br /> \u039f\u03a5 \u039b\u03a5\u03a1\u03a5\u0392\u0391\u0398\u03a9\u039d \u0398\u0399\u039d\u0399\u0398 \u03a6\u0391\u039d\u0395 \u0392\u0391\u039b <br /> \u03a5\u03a3 \u039d\u0391\u0394\u03a9\u03a1 \u03a3\u03a9\u03a3\u0399\u03a0\u0391\u03a4\u0399\u039f\u03a3 \u0392\u03a5\u039d \u0396\u039f\u03a0\u03a5\u03a1\u039f\u03a3 <br /> \u03a3\u0391\u039c\u03a9 \u039a\u039f\u03a5\u039b\u03a9 \u0392\u0391\u03a1\u0391\u03a7\u03a9 || l\u02bedn lb\u02bfl \u1e25mn <br />wlrbtn tnt pn b\u02bfl <br />\u02be\u0161 ndr S. bn Z. <br />\u0161m\u02be kl\u02be brk\u02be \n|-\n! colspan=2 | Translation\n|-\n| colspan=2 align=center| To the master [[Baal Hammon]]<br />and to our mistress [[Tanit]], the face of [[Baal]],<br />[that] which consecrated Sosipatius, son of Zopyrus.<br />He heard his voice and blessed him.\n|}\n\n==Survival and influences of Punic==\n{{main|Punic language}}\nThe significantly-divergent later form of the language that was spoken in the [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrian]] Phoenician colony of [[Carthage]] is known as Punic and remained in use there for considerably longer than Phoenician did in Phoenicia itself by arguably surviving into [[Augustine of Hippo]]'s time. The Punic throughout its existence co-existed with the [[Berber language]] which is native to [[Tunisia]] (Including Carthage) and North Africa. Punic disappeared some time after the destruction of Carthage by the Romans and the Berbers. It is possible that Punic may have survived the [[Muslim conquest of the Maghreb]] in some small isolated area: the geographer [[al-Bakri]] describes a people speaking a language that was not [[Berber language|Berber]], [[Latin]] or [[Coptic language|Coptic]] in the city of [[Sirte]] in rural [[Ifriqiya]], a region in which spoken Punic survived well past its written use.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.let.leidenuniv.nl/vtw/jongeling/latpun/LPINTRO.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-08-25 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051109091842/http://www.let.leidenuniv.nl/vtw/jongeling/LATPUN/LPINTRO.htm |archivedate=2005-11-09 |df= }}</ref> However, it is likely that arabization of the Punics was facilitated by their language belonging to the same group (both being [[Semitic languages]]) as that of the conquerors and thus having many grammatical and lexical similarities. Most Punic speakers may have been linguistically Berberized and/or Latinized after the fall of Carthage.\n\nThe ancient Libyco-Berber alphabet that is still in irregular use by modern Berber groups such as the [[Tuareg people|Tuareg]] is known by the native name [[Tifinagh]], possibly a derived form of a cognate of the name \"Punic\".{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} Still, a direct derivation from the Phoenician-Punic script is debated and far from established since the two writing systems are very different. As far as language (not the script) is concerned, some borrowings from Punic appear in modern Berber dialects: one interesting example is ''agadir'' \"wall\" from Punic ''gader''.\n\nPerhaps the most interesting case of Punic influence is that of the name of [[Hispania]] (the [[Iberian Peninsula]], comprising [[Portugal]] and [[Spain]]), which, according to one of the theories, is derived from the Punic ''I-Shaphan'' meaning \"coast of [[hyrax]]es\", in turn a misidentification on the part of Phoenician explorers of its numerous [[rabbit]]s as hyraxes.{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}} Another case is the name of a tribe of hostile \"hairy people\" that [[Hanno the Navigator]] found in the [[Gulf of Guinea]]. The name given to those people by [[Hanno the Navigator]]'s interpreters was transmitted from Punic into Greek as ''gorillai'' and was applied in 1847 by [[Thomas S. Savage]] to the [[western gorilla]].\n\n==Surviving examples==\nPhoenician, together with Punic, is primarily known from approximately 10,000 surviving inscriptions,{{sfn|Lehmann|2013|p=209|ps=:Nearly two hundred years later the repertory of Phoenician-Punic epigraphy counts about 10.000 inscriptions from throughout the Mediterranean and its environs. Nevertheless, almost 150 years after Gesenius, Wolfgang R\u00f6llig bewailed once more that \"notwithstanding the welcome increase of textual material in the past decades, Phoenician probably remains the worst transmitted and least known of all Semitic languages.}} supplemented by occasional glosses in books written in other languages. In addition to their many inscriptions, the Phoenicians are believed to have left numerous other types of written sources, but most have not survived.{{quote|The Phoenician alphabetic script was easy to write on [[papyrus]] or [[parchment]] sheets, and the use of these materials explains why virtually no Phoenician writings \u2013 no history, no trading records \u2013 have come down to us. In their cities by the sea, the air and soil were damp, and papyrus and leather moldered and rotted away. Thus disappeared the literature of the people who taught a large portion of the earth's population to write. The only written documents of Phoenicians and [[Carthaginians]] are monumental inscriptions on stone, a few ephemeral letters or notes on pieces of broken pottery, and three fragmentary papyri. Thus, no Tyrian primary sources dating from [[Hiram I]]'s time are available.<ref>Lipi\u0144ski (1995), p.1321-1322</ref>}}\n\nRoman authors, such as [[Sallust]], allude to some books written in the [[Punic language]], but none have survived except occasionally in translation (e.g., Mago's treatise) or in snippets (e.g., in [[Plautus]]' plays). The [[Cippi of Melqart]], a [[bilingual inscription]] in Ancient Greek and Carthaginian discovered in [[Malta]] in 1694, was the key which allowed French scholar [[Jean-Jacques Barth\u00e9lemy]] to decipher and reconstruct the alphabet in 1758.{{sfn|Lehmann|2013}} Even as late as 1837 only 70 Phoenician inscriptions were known to scholars. These were compiled in [[Wilhelm Gesenius]]'s ''Scripturae linguaeque Phoeniciae monumenta'', which comprised all that was known of Phoenician by scholars at that time.{{quote|Basically, its core consists of the comprehensive edition, or re-edition of 70 Phoenician and some more non-Phoenician inscriptions... However, just to note the advances made in the nineteenth century, it is noteworthy that Gesenius\u2019 precursor Hamaker, in his Miscellanea Phoenicia of 1828, had only 13 inscriptions at his disposal. On the other hand only 30 years later the amount of Phoenician inscribed monuments had grown so enormously that Schr\u00f6der in his compendium ''Die ph\u00f6nizische Sprache. Entwurf einer Grammatik nebst Sprach- und Schriftproben'' of 1869 could state that Gesenius knew only a quarter of the material Schr\u00f6der had at hand himself.{{sfn|Lehmann|2013|p=240}}|sign=|source=}}\nSome key surviving inscriptions of Phoenician are:\n\n*[[Ahiram sarcophagus]]\n*[[Bodashtart]]\n*[[\u00c7inek\u00f6y inscription]]\n*[[Cippi of Melqart]]\n*[[Eshmunazar II sarcophagus]]\n*[[Karatepe]]\n*[[Kilamuwa Stela]]\n*[[Nora Stone]]\n*[[Pyrgi Tablets]]\n*[[Temple of Eshmun]]\n\nSince [[Pyrgi Tablets|bilingual tablets]] with inscriptions in both [[Etruscan language|Etruscan]] and Phoenician dating from around 500 BC were found in 1964, more Etruscan has been deciphered through comparison to the more fully understood Phoenician.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Punic language]]\n*[[Phoenician alphabet]]\n*[[Emerald Tablet]]\n*[[Extinct language]]\n*[[List of extinct languages of Asia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{NIE Poster|Ph\u0153nician Language}}\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=yes |others=yes |about=yes |label=Phoenician language\n  |viaf= |lccn= |lcheading= |wikititle= }}\n*Fox, Joshua. \"A Sequence of Vowel Shifts in Phoenician and Other Languages.\" ''Journal of Near Eastern Studies'' 55, no. 1 (1996): 37-47. https://www.jstor.org/stable/545378.\n* {{cite book |last=Hackett |first=Joe Ann |year=2008 |chapter=Phoenician and Punic |title=The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia |editor-first=Roger D. |editor-last=Woodard |url=https://e-learning.tsu.ge/pluginfile.php/5868/mod_resource/content/0/dzveli_armosavluri_enebi_-ugarituli_punikuri_arameuli_ebrauli_arabuli.pdf |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=9780511486890 |doi=10.1017/CBO9780511486890 |chapter-url=https://e-learning.tsu.ge/pluginfile.php/5868/mod_resource/content/0/dzveli_armosavluri_enebi_-ugarituli_punikuri_arameuli_ebrauli_arabuli.pdf#page=104 |ref=harv}}\n*Holmstedt, Robert D., and Aaron Schade. ''Linguistic Studies In Phoenician: In Memory of J. Brian Peckham''. Winona Lake, IN: Eisenbrauns, 2013.\n*Krahmalkov, Charles R. ''A Phoenician-Punic Grammar''. Leiden: Brill, 2001.\n*Schmitz, Philip C. \"Phoenician-Punic Grammar and Lexicography in the New Millennium.\" ''Journal of the American Oriental Society'' 124, no. 3 (2004): 533-47. {{doi|10.2307/4132279.Copy}}\n*Segert, S. ''A Grammar of Phoenician and Punic''. M\u00fcnchen: C.H. Beck, 1976.\n* {{cite book |last=Segert |first=Stanislav |author-link=Stanislav Segert |chapter=Phoenician and the Eastern Canaanite languages |editor-first=Robert |editor-last=Hetzron |title=The Semitic Languages |date=October 1997 |isbn=9780415057677 |doi=10.4324/9781315002682.ch10 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |ref=harv|doi-broken-date=2020-03-12 |chapter-url=https://www.routledgehandbooks.com/doi/10.4324/9781315002682.ch10}}\n* {{cite book |last=Segert |first=Stanislav |author-link=Stanislav Segert |date=30 June 1997 |chapter=Phoenician and Punic phonology |title=Phonologies of Asia and Africa: (including the Caucasus) |editor-first=Alan S. |editor-last=Kaye |editor2-first=Peter T. |editor2-last=Daniels |chapter-url=https://books.google.es/books?id=T6jmziooEk0C&printsec=frontcover |publisher=[[Eisenbrauns]] |pages=1041 |isbn=9781575060194 |jstor=417482 |ref=harv}}\n*Tomback, Richard S. ''A Comparative Semitic Lexicon of the Phoenician and Punic Languages''. Missoula, MT: Scholars Press for the Society of Biblical Literature, 1978.\n*Tribulato, Olga. ''Language and Linguistic Contact In Ancient Sicily''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2012.\n*Woodard, Roger D. ''The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2008.\n\n{{Semitic languages |expanded=Northwest}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phoenician Language}}\n[[Category:Phoenician inscriptions]]\n[[Category:Phoenician language]]\n[[Category:Canaanite languages]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of Asia]]\n[[Category:Languages attested from the 11th century BC]]\n[[Category:Languages extinct in the 5th century BC]]\n[[Category:Languages of Sicily]]\n", "name_user": "Neutral0814", "label": "safe", "comment": "lead section: missing \"and\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoenician_language"}
{"title_page": "A Crow Looked at Me", "text_new": "{{Short description|8th Mount Eerie album}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Crow Looked at Me\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Mount Eerie]]\n| cover      = Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked at Me.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        = Male hand holding the [[Joanne Kyger]] poem \"Night Palace\" in the foreground. Background is of a house illuminated by an orange light\n| released   = {{startdate|2017|3|24}}\n| recorded   = August 31&nbsp;\u2013 December 6, 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Home recording]], [[Anacortes, Washington]]\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Indie folk]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=41|s=30}}\n| label      = P.W. Elverum & Sun\n| producer   = [[Phil Elverum]]\n| prev_title = [[Sauna (Mount Eerie album)|Sauna]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Now Only]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = A Crow Looked at Me\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Real Death\n | single1date = January 18, 2017\n | single2     = Ravens\n | single2date = February 15, 2017\n}}\n}}\n'''''A Crow Looked at Me''''' is the eighth studio album by [[Mount Eerie]], the solo project of American musician [[Phil Elverum]], released on March 24 2017 on Elverum's own label, P.W. Elverum & Sun. It is a [[concept album]] about the death of Elverum's wife, the Canadian cartoonist and musician [[Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e]]. The album was written and produced entirely by Elverum, who recorded it using mostly Castr\u00e9e's instruments in the room in which she died. A departure from Elverum's previous work, ''A Crow Looked at Me'' features minimal production and sparse instrumentation alongside lyrics that tell of Castr\u00e9e's illness and death, and Elverum's ensuing grief.\n\nPrior to the release of the album, Elverum released two singles, \"Real Death\" and \"Ravens\", released on January 18, 2017, and February 15, 2017, respectively. ''A Crow Looked at Me'' was an immediate and widespread critical success, appearing on numerous year-end lists. In the years following its release, the album has appeared in multiple decade-end lists. Some critics found that due to the album's personal nature, reviewing it felt difficult and disrespectful.\n\n==Background and composition==\n[[File:Gary Snyder, Mark Kozelek, Julie Doiron, Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd.jpg|thumb|left|250x250px|From left to right: Poet Gary Snyder, American musician Mark Kozelek, Norwegian writter Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd and Canadian singer-songwriter Julie Doiron, all of which Phil Elverum took inspiration from]]\n\nIn 2015, [[Phil Elverum]]'s wife, Canadian cartoonist and musician [[Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e]], was diagnosed with [[pancreatic cancer]] four months after the birth of their first child. Castr\u00e9e died at their home on July 9, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoo|first1=Noah|title=Genevi\u00e8ve Elverum Has Died|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/66697-genevieve-elverum-has-died|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=July 10, 2016|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Taking inspiration from the [[Gary Snyder]] poem \"Go Now\",<ref name=\"exclaim_gormely\">{{cite web |last1=Gormely |first1=Ian |title=Microphones, Mount Eerie and Melancholy: The Career of Phil Elverum |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/microphones_mount_eerie_and_melancholy_the_career_of_phil_elverum |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate= November 16, 2018 |date=November 5, 2018}}</ref> Elverum realised that he did not have to find any meaning in Castr\u00e9e's death but could write songs that described the experience.<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite web |last1=Kornhaber |first1=Spencer |title=The Pointlessness and Promise of Art After Death |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/03/mount-eerie-now-only-interview-phil-elverum/555485/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> He also found inspiration in the work of Canadian singer-songwriter [[Julie Doiron]], American singer-songwriter [[Will Oldham]], American rock band [[Sun Kil Moon]] and Norwegian author [[Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd]].<ref name=\"pearce\">{{cite web |last1=Pearce |first1=Sheldon |title=Mount Eerie Announces New Album, Shares New Song 'Real Death' |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/70642-mount-eerie-announces-new-album-shares-new-song-real-death-listen/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 21, 2018 |date=January 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"self-titled\">{{cite web|url=http://www.self-titledmag.com/new-mount-eerie-album-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie Reveals Deeply Personal Album, A Crow Looked At Me|magazine=Self-Titled|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Elverum felt compelled to make the album as he found that the art he used to treasured was ineffective at helping him cope, saying to Donovan Burtan of ''[[Cult MTL]]'' that \"all the things that used to bring me a sense of meaning and depth and comfort, all these books in the house of poetry, philosophy and everything \u2014 all of it was just empty and useless\".<ref name=\"cult\"/> \n\n{{Quote box \n|width=270px\n|align=right\n|title=\n|author=\n|salign=right\n|bgcolor=#f6f7f0\n|tstyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:100%;\n|quote =\"Songs in the future. No reverb. Close and direct. Dense with easy words. Don\u2019t rely on hanging emotions or drawn-out notes. Engage the mind\u2019s chewing teeth. Say everything as it is. No metaphors. Resist big-picture reflections.\" An example of the notes which Elverum wrote.<ref name=\"Stosuy\" />}}\n\nAfter Castree's death, Elverum considered retiring from music as a whole and becoming a full time father but a trip to [[Haida Gwaii]] inspired \nhim to write notes which would become the album (alongside the notes that he had written during Castr\u00e9e's illness and treatment).<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/><ref>{{Cite podcast|host=Jesse Thorn|title=Werner Herzog and Mount Eerie\u2019s Phil Elverum|website=Maxiumin Fun|publisher=Bullseye with Jesse Thorn|date=April 24, 2017|time=24:37-25:20|url=https://maximumfun.org/episodes/bullseye-with-jesse-thorn/bullseye-jesse-thorn-werner-herzog-and-phil-elverum/|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> Elverum recorded the album from August 31, 2016 to December 6 of the same year at his house in [[Anacortes, Washington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.folkradio.co.uk/2017/01/mount-eerie-real-death/|title=Mount Eerie Shares Song From New Album: Real Death|website=Folk Radio|last=Gallacher|first=Alex|date=January 26, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"now\"/> He wrote the songs over a six-week period<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> starting in September 2016.<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\">{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Jayson |title=Death Is Real: Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Copes With Unspeakable Tragedy |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/profile/10034-death-is-real-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-copes-with-unspeakable-tragedy/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 13, 2017}}</ref> He wrote the lyrics down longhand on her notepaper<ref name=\"tmt\">{{cite web |last1=Lin |first1=Marvin |title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked At Me |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/mount-eerie-crow-looked-me |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]| date=2017 |accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> and recorded the songs in the room where she died using an acoustic guitar, one microphone and a laptop computer<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> alongside some of Castr\u00e9e's own instruments.<ref name=\"cos\"/> Since he had become the primary carer for his daughter, Elverum recorded the songs at night while his daughter was asleep{{efn|Elverum recorded some of the songs with her sleeping 10 feet away.<ref name=\"LARB\"/>}} or during times when she was visiting friends.<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> In a interview Elverum talked about how he would choose recording over self care: \"I can either have a shower for the first time in, like, two weeks or I can write down these ideas that have been bursting in my head.\"<ref name=\"lie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.liveineverett.com/blog//an-interview-with-phil-elverum-of-mount-eeriethe-microphones|title=An Interview With Phil Elverum of Mount Eerie|website=Live In Everett|last1=Porter|first1=Christa|last2=Porter|first2=Richard|date=March 19, 2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nElverum stated that the songs \"poured out quickly in the fall, watching the days grey over and watching the neighbors across the alley tear down and rebuild their house\", with him filling the pages of his notebook with \"formless, no-rhythm, no-meter, no-melody blob of words\".<ref name=\"abc\"/><ref name=\"fact_announce\"/> Elverum said he made and released the record in order to \"multiply my voice saying that I love her. I want it known.\" and draw a distinction between \"art and music versus the actual experience of life\".<ref name=\"fact_announce\">{{cite web |last1=Bowe |first1=Miles |title=Mount Eerie addresses his wife's death on new album A Crow Looked At Me |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/01/25/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-crow-looked-at-me-real-death/ |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=January 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cult\"/> When writing the album Elverum intended for the songs to have a \"sort of hyper-intimate, no restraint\" quality to them and to be more philosophical in nature<ref name=\"observer\"/> but devoid of symbolism and distinct from the more existential themes of his earlier work.<ref>{{Cite podcast|host=Jesse Thorn|title=Werner Herzog and Mount Eerie\u2019s Phil Elverum|website=Maxiumin Fun|publisher=Bullseye with Jesse Thorn|date=April 24, 2017|time=29:30-30:30|url=https://maximumfun.org/episodes/bullseye-with-jesse-thorn/bullseye-jesse-thorn-werner-herzog-and-phil-elverum/|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Concordian\">{{cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2017/09/how-mount-eerie-copes-with-personal-grief/|title=How Mount Eerie copes with personal grief|publisher=[[The Concordian (Montreal)|The Concordian]]|last=Walker|first=Erin|date=September 12, 2017|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> Elverum revealed in an interview that he did not have a goal in mind while creating the album, saying instead that he was in an \"unpremeditated way going with the flow\".<ref name=\"cult\">{{cite web|url=https://cultmtl.com/2017/09/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-interview/|title=Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum on music and grief|website=[[Cult MTL]]|last=Burtan|first=Donovan|date=September 12, 2017|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He has also stated that he doesn't view the album as tribute or even being about Castr\u00e9e believing if he were to make a tribute it would be ineffective at capturing who Castr\u00e9e was, instead viewing the album as a documentation of his grief and of him \"saying all the heavy stuff with no regard for other people\u2019s sensitivity or unwillingness\", detached from Castr\u00e9e.<ref name=\"cult\"/><ref name=\"abc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/doublej/music-reads/features/mount-eerie-is-not-just-poking-at-sadness/10266514|title=Mount Eerie is not just poking at sadness|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]|date=January 23, 2018|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LARB\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.lareviewofbooks.org/interviews/un-treasured-time-conversation-phil-elverum/|title=Un-treasured Time: A Conversation with Phil Elverum|publisher=[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]|last=Marrs|first=Cypress|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Elverum found the recording process as a positive, calling it \"therapeutic\" and saying it felt as if he was \"hanging out with her [Castr\u00e9e]\" and feeling by the end as if he had healed.<ref name=\"Mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2997421/phil-elverum-mount-eerie-interview/|title=Phil Elverum On Life, Death And Meaninglessness|publisher=[[MTV]]|last=Garvey|first=Meghan|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"kexp\">{{cite web|url=https://kexp.org/read/2020/2/13/music-heals-phil-elverum-expressing-grief-through-music-and-remembering-his-late-wife-genevieve-castree/|title=Music Heals: Phil Elverum on Expressing Grief Through Music and Remembering His Late Wife Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e|website=Kexp|last=Fox|first=Emily|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe cover of the album features a photograph of the [[Joanne Kyger]]{{efn|Kyger died of lung cancer two days before the album's release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Joanne-Kyger-trailblazing-Beat-poet-dies-at-82-11021799.php|title=Joanne Kyger, trailblazing Beat poet, dies at 82|author=John McMurtie|accessdate=March 25, 2017|date=March 23, 2017|publisher=[[San Francisco Gate]]}}</ref>}} poem \"Night Palace\", which Castr\u00e9e had pinned above her desk.<ref name=\"observer\">{{cite web |last1=Joffe |first1=Justin |title=Beyond Grief: How Mount Eerie Made an Album About His Wife's Death |url=https://observer.com/2017/03/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-interview/ |website=[[observer.com|Observer]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> Elverum had taken the photograph while he was cleaning out her room after she died and realised that the poem encapsulated the theme of the album. Castr\u00e9e's copy of [[Herg\u00e9]]'s ''[[Tintin in Tibet]]'' can be seen in the background.<ref name=\"bandcamp\">{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Erin Lyndal |title=Mount Eerie on Intimate Grief and the Creative Impulse |url=https://daily.bandcamp.com/2017/03/21/mount-eerie-interview/ |publisher=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=November 29, 2018|date=March 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n[[File:Mount_Eerie,_Real_Death.ogg|thumb|260x300px|right|The album opener introduces the theme that \"death is real\" which Elverum once said \"could be the name\" of the album.<ref name=\"fact_announce\" />]]\n\nThe lyrics are delivered in a [[Sprechgesang|speak-singing]], conversational manner<ref name=\"SC\"/> and deal with Castr\u00e9e's illness and death, and Elverum's ensuing grief, which is the thematic concept of the album along with the theme of there being nothing to learn or gain from death.<ref name=\"exclaim_after\">{{cite web |last1=Gormely |first1=Ian |title=Phil Elverum Reveals How Mount Eerie Live Album '(After)' Puts Mourning to Rest |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/phil_elverum_reveals_how_mount_eerie_live_album_after_puts_mourning_to_rest |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=September 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|last1=Gotrich|first1=Lars|title=Stream Mount Eerie's Heartbreaking New Album, 'A Crow Looked At Me'|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/03/16/520013269/first-listen-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me |publisher=[[NPR]]|date=March 16, 2017|accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"arena\">{{cite web|url=https://arena.com/article/a-crow-looked-at-me-mount-eerie|title=A Crow Looked At Me: Death and Nature on New Mount Eerie Album|website=Arena|last=Sanna|first=Jacopo|date=March 30, 2017|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Elverum's vocals have been described as \"weak and shy\" which \"show us an artist that is completely consumed by a cruel, unforgiving world\".<ref name=\"bch\"/> The words take the form of a diary with Elverum intending for each song to reflect a time in his grieving, and include references to specific events and dates throughout. Elverum said that \"each song is anchored to a very specific moment\".<ref name=\"Stosuy\" /> Writer Thomas Britt wrote that this showcases \"the way that death hangs over each day that follows\".<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> Each song refers to Castr\u00e9e, sometimes directly by name, Elverum frequently uses pronouns such as \"our\" when referring to Castr\u00e9e despite her absence, one critic noted that this is because Elverum \"struggles to adjust to the undesired change\".<ref name=\"tmt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> The final song \"Crow\" is however addressed prominently to their daughter.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |last1=Caramanica |first1=Jon |title=The Sound of Sadness Overwhelms and Inspires Mount Eerie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/22/arts/music/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate= November 28, 2018 |date=March 22, 2017}}</ref> The lyrics have been described to \"combine emotional intimacy and tonal frankness to a degree rarely heard in contemporary music\" and as \"unspooling pieces of prose\"<ref name=\"New Yorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/in-a-room-listening-to-phil-elverum-sing-about-his-wifes-death|title=In A Room Listening To Phil Elverum Sing About His Wife's Death|website=[[The New Yorker]]|last=Baker|first=Peter C|date=September 6, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/nov/14/mount-eerie-review-phil-elverum|title=Mount Eerie review \u2013 truth defeats beauty on stark songs of death|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Hann|first=Michael|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The songwriting has been described as \"brilliant examples of breaking the fourth wall\" and that the term itself does not align with the style of the material claiming it's \"too precise\", noting the blurred lines \"between singing, speaking and raw emotional data dump.\"<ref name=\"berkle\">{{cite web|url=https://online.berklee.edu/takenote/mount-eerie-expressing-emptiness-in-songwriting/|title=Death is Real: Mount Eerie and the Art of Expressing 'Emptiness' through Songwriting|publisher=[[Berklee]]|last=Zavada|first=Eric|date=2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt\"/>\n\nOpening track \"Real Death\" features spoken-word vocals which are \"whispered from a void of hurt\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.treblezine.com/34446-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review/|title=Mount Eerie A Crow Looked At Me Review|website=Treblezine|last=Roesler|first=Brian|date=2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The song concerns itself with the \"impossibility of representing loss\", \"the hopelessness that comes after the death\" and \"highlights the inherent permanence of death with strikingly plain descriptions of the last few days and weeks of Castr\u00e9e\u2019s life\".<ref name=\"Kurki\">{{cite journal|last=Hilla|first=Kurki|date=2018|title=Notes on loss and photography|url=https://aaltodoc.aalto.fi/handle/123456789/31397|publisher=[[Aalto University]]|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"the cowl\"/><ref name=\"bch\">{{cite web|url=https://bcheights.com/2017/04/05/emotions-fly-crow-looked/|title=Emotions Fly in \u2018A Crow Looked At Me\u2019|website=The Heights|last=Guarna|first=Tomas|date=April 5, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> The song features the opening lyrics, \"death is real\" with the theme continuing throughout the record (along with the phrase itself).<ref name=\"wuog\">{{cite web|url=http://wuog.org/index.php/2017/04/04/featured-review-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked at Me|website=WUOG|last=Elder|first=Drew|date=April 4, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"allmusic\"/><ref name=\"nyt\"/> The song also introduces the theme of the album not being an artistic statement, with Phillip Green of Cisternyard Media speculating the reason behinds Elverum's aversion is that to do so \"would be taking advantage of Genevieve's passing\".<ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> The song also refers to Elverum opening mail packages addressed to Castr\u00e9e that were delivered after her death, with one critic saying that the moment \"limns the space between the living and the dead\"<ref name=\"nyt\"/> Elverum discusses scattering Castr\u00e9e's ashes and the house they intended to build on \"Seaweed\". It is composed of \"warm\" guitar plucking, \"discordant\" piano and \"hollowed\" [[bass guitar|bass]].<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> The song also introduces the themes of Castr\u00e9e's \"Spiritual omnipresence\", Castree \"surviving\" through their daughter and Elverum remembering her beyond the physical, choosing to immortalize her as the sunset, instead of as ashes.{{efn|Elverum also remembers her as a foxglove in [[Haida Gwaii]] and a fly in his house.<ref name=\"arena\"/>}}<ref name=\"allmusic\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> Writer Molly Beauchemin stated that the song \"stands apart for its crushing invocation of nature as a place of solace and refuge\u2013 a place to see purpose in the midst of loss\"<ref name=\"Garden\">{{cite web|url=https://gardencollage.com/heal/mind-spirit/mount-eeries-seaweed-heartbreaking-reflection-love-death-nature/|title=Mount Eerie's 'Seaweed' Is A Heartbreaking Reflection on Love, Death, and Nature|magazine=Garden Collage|last=Beauchemin|first=Molly|date=May 28, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> \"Ravens\" describes Elverum giving away Castr\u00e9e's clothes.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> \"Ravens\" standing apart from the other songs features multiple tempo changes.{{efn|\"Soria Moria\" also features tempo changes.<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/>}}<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> It has been described as the centrepiece of the album with its \"hushed acoustic guitar, ominous piano notes, and stark reminders of Genevi\u00e8ve's absence\"<ref name=\"capc\">{{cite web|url=https://christandpopculture.com/mount-eeries-crow-looked-confronts-horror-death/|title=Mount Eerie's A Crow Looked at Me Confronts the Horror of Death|website=Christ and Pop Culture|last=Morehead|first=Jason|date=April 14, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Sam Sodomsky of [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] called the song a \"seven-minute exploration of the horrors of this world\".<ref name=\"pitchfork ravens\" /> The track \"Forest Fire\" describes Elverum's feelings of death, decay, and absurdity in relation to the world around him. As well as apologizing to Castr\u00e9e for attempting to move on. and wondering how he will live without Castr\u00e9e.<ref name=\"nyt2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/04/magazine/new-sentences-from-forest-fire-by-mount-eerie.html|title=New Sentences: From 'Forest Fire,' by Mount Eerie|website=[[The New York Times]]|last=Abebe|first=Nitsuh|date=April 4, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"No ripcord\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.noripcord.com/reviews/music/mount-eerie/crow-looked-me|title=A Crow Looked at Me|website=No Ripcord|last=Smith|first=Matthew|date=March 23, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"bch\"/> Nitsuh Abebe of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described the song as a \"perfectly accurate description of our actual world\".<ref name=\"nyt2\"/> \"Swims\" details Elverum's experiences with [[grief counselling]] and the sudden death of his counsellor in light of Castr\u00e9e's death. It was described by one reviewer as \"one of the most heart wrenching songs created\".<ref name=\"GA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.getalternative.com/review-mount-eerie-crow-looked/|title=Review: Mount Eerie \u2013 \u2018A Crow Looked At Me\u2019|website=The Alternative|last=Gonzalez|first=Sean|date=April 7, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> It features minimal guitars, simple piano chords, \"echo-laden\" bass, \"[[lo-fi music|lo-fi]] soundscapes\" and what has been described as \"Elverum's most naked vocal performance\".<ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> \n\n[[Image:Theodor Kittelsen, Soria Moria.jpg|right|thumb|260x280px|''Soria Moria'' by [[Theodor Kittelsen]] (1881) inspired the track by the same name]]\n\n\"My Chasm\" demonstrates Elverum's difficulty in talking about his loss in public and has been described as \"a tribute to their everlasting love\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"fact_announce\" /> It features electronic instrumentation with piano accompaniment.<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> Elverum's vocal performance was described as having \"identifiable pain\" which is almost palpable.<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> \"When I Take the Garbage Out At Night\" invokes mundane imagery with one writer drawing comparisons to [[Sun Kil Moon]]'s ''[[Benji (album)|Benji]]''.<ref name=\"SC\"/> \"Emptiness pt. 2\" deals with the idea of \"conceptual emptiness\" with Elverum comparing his grief to \"climbing up a mountain in complete loneliness\".<ref name=\"now\">{{cite news|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/mount-eerie-album-review/|title=Mount Eerie's A Crow Looked At Me is unsettlingly personal| newspaper=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]|last=Greene|first=Sarah|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"bch\"/> Thomas Britt of ''[[PopMatters]]'' wrote that \"This self-reflexive commentary reframes even the most powerful pictures of wind-hewn, frosted, blackened solitude in the past Microphones/Mount Eerie songbook as products of comparative comfort; luxuries of imagination\".<ref name=\"popmatters\" /> Elverum discusses the fading familiar memories of Castr\u00e9e on the song \"Toothbrush/Trash\" has been described as a \"horrible realization that time will not relent\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/> as well as the \"most uplifting track\" on the album which conveys \"the paradoxically happy and miserable state of acceptance\".<ref name=\"radio\">{{cite web|url=https://radioutd.com/blog/2017/03/mount-eerie-crow-looked/|title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked at Me|website=Radio UTD|last=Hardaway|first=Grant|date=March 26, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Its sudden sound cue of a door closing (which Elverum recorded himself) was described by Brian Roesler as \"a haunted chamber of memory and connection that now seems more real than ever\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> The track \"Soria Moria\" takes its name from a painting of the [[Soria Moria Castle|same name]] by [[Theodor Kittelsen]], incorporates elements of [[black metal]]<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> and details Elverum's relationship with Castr\u00e9e before her death as well as referencing Elverum's time in a Norwegian cabin, in which he wrote his 2008 album [[Dawn (Mount Eerie album)|''Dawn'']] as well as interpolating the lyric \"I went back to feel alone there\" from his 2001 song [[The Glow Pt. 2|\"The Moon\"]].<ref name=\"brainwashed\">{{cite web|url=https://brainwashed.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7529:phil-elverum-qdawn-winter-journalq&catid=17:books&Itemid=134|title=Phil Elverum, 'Dawn: Winter Journal'|website=Brainwash|last=Spencer|first=Matthew|date=May 2, 2009|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"npr\" /> The final song \"Crow\" is addressed to his daughter as Elverum ponders all the ways in which Castr\u00e9e lives on, such as a crow that was following them on a hike in the Pacific Northwest. It's the only song to have references to events beyond Elverum's life, as he describes the world as \"Smoldering and fascist\", comments which were inspired by the [[2016 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"Mtv\"/> The song has been described as an \"epilogue of sorts\" which \"offers a new and hopeful perspective\" and as \"One of the more poetic tracks on the album\"<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\">{{cite web|url=https://cisternyard.com/2017/03/30/24689/|title='A Crow Looked at Me' By Mount Eerie \u2013 An Album Review|website=Cistern Yard|last=Greene|first=Phillip|date=March 30, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nMany of the lyrics feature references to nature<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> with one reviewer noting that \"tragedy hasn't stopped [Elverum] from noticing the world; if anything, it seems to have pried his eyes open for good.\"<ref name=\"Powell\"/> In her review for student newspaper \"The Cowl\" Alexus Jais noted how the songs \"seem to imply that Elverum is frustrated with a common trend to romanticize death and make it seem easier and more beautiful than perhaps it really is\".<ref name=\"the cowl\">{{cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.providence.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3182&context=cowl|title=Album Review: A Crow Looked at Me|publisher=The Cowl|last=Jais|first=Alexis|date=October 5, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Musically, the album is reminiscent of his 2008 work ''[[Lost Wisdom]]''<ref name=\"now\" /> with the songs featuring sparse instrumentation and songwriting with acoustic guitar, simple percussion, no [[chorus (song)|choruses]] and \"barely any melodies\". This was a result of Elverum wishing to move away from his earlier, more \"artistically challenging\" work, which was characterised by \"harsh tones\" and \"complicated chords\".<ref name=\"abc\"/><ref name=\"portlandmercury\">{{cite web |last1=Salmon |first1=Ben |title=On A Crow Looked at Me, Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Processes the Death of His Wife |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/music/2017/04/12/18944358/on-a-crow-looked-at-me-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-processes-the-death-of-his-wife |website=[[The Portland Mercury|Portland Mercury]] |accessdate=December 18, 2018 |date=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/><ref name=\"stereogum week\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1930429/album-of-the-week-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/franchises/album-of-the-week/|title=Album Of The Week: Mount Eerie A Crow Looked At Me|website=[[Stereogum]]|last=Breihan|first=Tom|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> The sparse nature of the album lead to Elverum referring to the album as \"barely music\".<ref name=\"Powell\"/> The album is less musically dark in comparison to the rest of the [[Mount Eerie #Discography|Mount Eerie discography]].<ref name=\"arena\"/> Elverum wanted to release the album quickly, so he used minimal [[Record producer|production]].<ref name=\"beatroute\">{{cite web |title=A Crow Looked at Me Gives Mount Eerie a Worthy Eulogy |url=https://archive.beatroute.ca/2017/08/12/crow-looked-gives-mount-eerie-worthy-eulogy/ |website=Beatroute|date=August 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref> This was Elverum's first album to be entirely produced on a computer.<ref>{{cite podcast|host=Tom Power|title=July 4: How music helped Phil Elverum grieve his wife's death|website=WNYC|date=July 4, 2017|time=10:12-10:30|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/july-4-how-music-helped-phil-elverum-grieve-his-wifes-death/|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\n{{Quote box \n|width=250px\n|align=right\n|title=Night Palace\n|author=Joanne Kyger\n|salign=right\n|bgcolor=#f6f7f0\n|tstyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:100%;\n|quote =<poem>\nThe best thing about the past\nis that it's over\nwhen you die.\nyou wake up\nfrom the dream\nthat's your life.\n\nThen you grow up\nand get to be post human\nin a past that keeps happening\nahead of you\n</poem>\n}}\n\nElverum considered not releasing the album at all, or changing his band name entirely but ultimately decided to do neither.<ref name=\"Stosuy\">{{cite web |last1=Stosuy |first1=Brandon |title=Phil Elverum on creating art from grief |url=https://thecreativeindependent.com/people/phil-elverum-on-creating-art-from-grief/ |website=The Creative Independent |accessdate=December 10, 2018 |date=March 15, 2017}}</ref> He had originally planned for a small scale release of the record on his own website, but as the album took shape he felt that it was good and wanted it to reach a wider audience.<ref name=\"noisey\">{{cite web |last1=Currin |first1=Grayson |title=How Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Faced Grief on His Devastating New Album |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/wn9z54/a-conversation-with-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-on-his-devastating-new-album |website=[[Vice_(magazine)#Website|Vice]]|date=March 28, 2017 |accessdate=November 19, 2018}}</ref> Despite this he still found releasing the album and promoting it to be \"gross and weird from a lot of perspectives\".<ref name=\"Stosuy\" /> On January 5, 2017, he announced that he would go on tour, and release a new album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoo|first1=Noah|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/70707-phil-elverum-please-dont-come-to-tomorrows-mount-eerie-show/|title=Phil Elverum: 'Please Don't Come' to Tomorrow's Mount Eerie Show|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> The next day, he played his first concert since September 2014 at a record store in [[Anacortes, Washington]]. Elverum, while choosing to perform, also asked fans to stay away as the response was \"overwhelming\" and the store could only hold 50 people.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Strauss|first1=Matthew|title=Mount Eerie Performing New Music at First Show in 2 Years|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/70637-mount-eerie-performing-new-music-at-first-show-in-2-years/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=December 30, 2016|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Elverum performed the show with his eyes closed and left immediately afterwards.<ref name=\"larecord\">{{cite web |last1=Child |first1=Tom |title=Mount Eerie: Stay Sincere |url=http://larecord.com/archive/2017/04/10/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-phil-elverum-interview |website=[[L.A. Record]] |accessdate= November 21, 2018 |date=April 10, 2017}}</ref> The first single from ''A Crow Looked at Me'', \"Real Death\", was released on P.W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.'s [[SoundCloud]] page on January 18, 2017, to widespread acclaim, netting the \"Best New Track\" distinction from ''Pitchfork''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Currin|first1=Grayson|title='Real Death' by Mount Eerie Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18708-mount-eerie-real-death/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"paste single\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/mount-eerie/mount-eerie-releases-music-video-for-ravens-announ/|title=Mount Eerie Releases Devastating 'Ravens' Video, Announces West Coast Tour Dates|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Rohrback|first=Paul|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The second single, \"Ravens\", was released on February 15, 2017, alongside a music video uploaded to Mount Eerie's official [[YouTube]] account, again earning the \"Best New Track\" distinction from ''Pitchfork'', writing that \"Elverum makes no attempts to find metaphor or meaning; when he sees two ravens flying overhead, he knows it's an omen, but he can't say what for.\"<ref name=\"pitchfork ravens\">{{cite web|last1=Sodomsky|first1=Sam|title='Ravens' by Mount Eerie Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18780-mount-eerie-ravens/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"paste single\"/> Following the release of the album, Elverum embarked on a North American tour in September 2017, playing solo shows accompanied only by his acoustic guitar in intimate venues that included \"concert halls, churches, and theaters\".<ref name=\"geslani\">{{cite web |last1=Geslani |first1=Michelle |title=Mount Eerie announces North American tour dates |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/05/mount-eerie-announces-north-american-tour-dates/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=May 31, 2017}}</ref> The tour was extended to include Europe in November 2017.<ref name=\"TMTsmart\">{{cite web |last1=Smart |first1=Dan |title=Mount Eerie announces European tour dates in November |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/mount-eerie-announces-european-tour-dates-november |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=September 20, 2017}}</ref> While performing at [[Jacobikerk]] as part of [[Le Guess Who?]] festival in [[Utrecht]], a sound engineer recorded Elverum's set without his knowledge. Elverum liked the recording so much that it was subsequently released as the live album ''[[(after)]]'' in 2018.<ref name=\"pitchforkafter\">{{cite web |last=Reese |first=Nathan |title=Mount Eerie: (after) |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/mount-eerie-after/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe tour received a positive reception. Jochan Embley of ''[[The Independent]]'' awarded the show performed at [[St John on Bethnal Green]] church five stars and wrote that Elverum \"plays and sings with such softness and space that you can hear the hum of his monitors as he does so\".<ref name=\"Independent Tour\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/mount-eerie-tour-a-crow-looked-at-me-london-tour-live-review-a8054051.html|title=Mount Eerie, St John on Bethnal Green, gig review: Beautiful art inspired by tragedy|website=[[The Independent]]|last=Embley|first=Jochan|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Adam O'Sullivan of the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' described the show as \"something truly remarkable, truly honest and something that those in attendance are unlikely ever to see again\".<ref name=\"es\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/mount-eerie-a-truly-remarkable-and-honest-portrayal-of-tragedy-a3716321.html|title=Mount Eerie at St John on Bethnal Green: A truly remarkable and honest portrayal of tragedy|publisher=[[Evening Standard]]|last=O'Sullivan|first=Adam|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> Woody Delaney of ''[[Loud and Quiet]]'' praised the show performed at Left Bank, Leeds calling it an \"experience so human, it serves to remind the audience to cherish the fragility of life, and more immediately the person sat next to them\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudandquiet.com/short/sobering-appreciation-comes-mount-eeries-devastating-grief/|title=The sobering appreciation that comes from Mount Eerie\u2019s devastating grief|publisher=[[Loud and Quiet]]|last=Delaney|first=Woody|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Aaron Badgley of ''Spill Magazine'' praised the show at the Great Hall, Toronto, Canada calling it \"one of the most memorable performances\" he has seen and concluding that \"to have the opportunity to see him do this live was one of those rare instances in life when you witnessed something truly important on stage\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spillmagazine.com/spill-live-review-mount-eerie-great-hall-toronto/|title=Spill Live Review: Mount Eerie @ Great Hall Toronto|publisher=Spill Magazine|last=Badgley|first=Aaron|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Sarah Greene, of ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now Toronto]]'' echoed similar sentiments describeing the show as \"painfullly intimate\" and stating that \"In his solo performance, Phil Elverum showed that both songwriting and grieving are an ongoing process\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/concert-reviews/mount-eerie-at-the-great-hall/|title=Mount Eerie's Great Hall concert was painfully intimate|magazine=[[Now (newspaper)|Now Toronto]]|last=Greene|first=Sarah|date=September 21, 2017|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> \n\nElverum found that due to the personal nature of the songs touring was difficult, saying it felt like he was \"going out there and re-enacting a trauma and charging people money for it\" and criticising the sense of voyeurism the audience part took in.<ref name=\"abc\"/> Elverum also did several interviews{{efn|Elverum was at one point doing five interviews in one day.<ref name=\"Portland 2\"/>}} which he found to be \"mentally draining\", although he did admit that he treated them as pseudo-[[therapy]] sessions noting how they were different from a typical [[Public Relations|PR]] campaign.<ref name=\"Portland 2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/music/2017/04/12/18944358/on-a-crow-looked-at-me-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-processes-the-death-of-his-wife|title=On A Crow Looked at Me, Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Processes the Death of His Wife|website=Portland Mercury|last=Salmon|first=Ben|date=April 12, 2017|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 8.8/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/8559/Mount-Eerie-A-Crow-Looked-at-Me.aspx|title=A Crow Looked at Me by Mount Eerie reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| MC = 93/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/a-crow-looked-at-me/mount-eerie|title=Reviews and Tracks for A Crow Looked at Me by Mount Eerie|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-crow-looked-at-me-mw0003032380|title=A Crow Looked at Me \u2013 Mount Eerie|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Phares|first=Heather|date=2017|accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/live/craig-finn-mount-eerie-pallbearer-and-more-weeks-m-252416|title=Mount Eerie confronts death on its saddest album to date|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Corcoran|first=Nina|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev3score = A\u2212<ref name=\"cos\">{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/03/album-review-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Sackllah|first=David|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4score = 9/10<ref name=\"exclaimfenech\">{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/mount_eerie-a_crow_looked_at_me|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Fenech|first=Zach|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|last=Male|first=Andrew|issue=284|date=July 2017|page=91}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n| rev6score = 9.2/10<ref name=\"paste\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/03/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review.html|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked At Me Review|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Fink|first=Matt|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 9.0/10<ref name=\"Powell\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22970-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked At Me|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Powell|first=Mike|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev8Score = 10/10<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[PopMatters]]|last=Britt|first=Thomas|date=March 20, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev9score = 9/10<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|journal=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|issue=240|date=May 2017|page=35}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' ([[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Expert Witness]])\n| rev10score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/8xvyqv/expert-witness-with-robert-christgau-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me|title=Robert Christgau on Mount Eerie's 'A Crow Looked at Me,' a Brutal Listen|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=January 27, 2018|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''A Crow Looked at Me'' received widespread critical acclaim upon release. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from [[music critic]]s, the album has received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 93, indicating \"universal acclaim\", based on 18 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave ''A Crow Looked At Me'' 8.8 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"adm\"/> Elverum found the album's reception \"reaffirming\", but was frustrated by those who viewed it as a tribute to his wife and felt uneasy about the album being public at all.<ref name=\"atlantic\"/><ref name=\"cult\"/> Heather Phares from [[AllMusic]] called the album \"remarkably powerful and pure\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''{{'}}s David Sackllah said that it was \"overwhelming and humbling\" and wrote that \"A Crow Looked at Me stands as a remarkable example of the restorative power of music, an intimate display of love, daring both in concept and execution.\"<ref name=\"cos\"/> Zack Fenech from ''[[Exclaim!]]'' said that \"this record possesses immense power to make listeners reflect on their own relationships and mortality. ''A Crow Looked at Me'' is a grim memento of the grand injustice of losing those most precious to us.\"<ref name=\"exclaimfenech\"/> [[Paste (magazine)|''Paste'']]{{'}}s Matt Fink said that it was \"beautifully and simply arranged, but it is not an entertaining album to listen to in any conventional sense, nor can it be shaken off easily. It is, however, the kind of album that makes all others seem frivolous\" and that \"there is no album quite like it.\"<ref name=\"paste\"/>\n\nBen Malkin from ''GIGsoup'' described the album \"art in its most pure, human form\", a \"showcase of weakness and cruel reality, prose of lost love,\" and \"perhaps the saddest album ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gigsoupmusic.com/reviews/album-reviews/mount-eerie-crow-looked/|title=Mount Eerie 'A Crow Looked at Me'|website=Gigsoup|last=Malkin|first=Ben|date=April 3, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In his review for ''[[Spectrum Culture]]'' John Paul said that \"Heartbreaking doesn't even begin to describe ''A Crow Looked at Me''\" and described the album as \"pure grief delivered in a voice in which you can hear the weight of loss\".<ref name=\"SC\">{{Cite web|url=https://spectrumculture.com/2017/03/28/mount-eerie/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|website=[[Spectrum Culture]]|last=Paul|first=John|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Jacopo Sanna of ''Arena Music'' claimed that ''A Crow Looked at Me'' is \"probably the most important album about death and loss ever recorded\".<ref name=\"Arena2\">{{cite web|url=https://arena.com/article/mount-eerie-and-everything-that-is-left-to-remember|title=Mount Eerie Explores Everything That's Left to Remember|website=Arena Music|last=Sanna|first=Jacopo|date=March 28, 2018|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Sarah Greene, writing for ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now Toronto]]'' described ''A Crow Looked At Me'' as \"a lovingly crafted album, with gentle melodies that linger in the air, pretty, memorable guitar lines and a subtle but persistent approach to percussion\" and concluded that despite it may being an uncomfortable and harrowing listen it was also a \"tribute to an amazing 13-year love story\".<ref name=\"now\" /> Brian Roesler, from ''Treblezine'', despite enjoying the record considerably, demanded that readers \"Don't call it art. Don't call it music even. Call it a documentation of suffering and loss as an experience, and treat it as such\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/>{{efn|A sentiment echoed by Elverum himself.<ref name=\"Powell\"/>}} In a [[essay]] written for ''[[The Spinoff]]'', Murdoch Stephens compared ''A Crow Looked At Me'' to the poetry of [[Auschwitz]] survivor [[Primo Levi]] and pondered how the listener should interact with a piece of art of such a visceral nature. He called Elverum \"the saddest musician in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/music/15-01-2018/how-to-listen-to-mount-eerie-the-saddest-musician-in-the-world/|title=How to listen to Mount Eerie, the saddest musician in the world|website=[[The Spinoff]]|last=Stephens|first=Murdoch|date=January 15, 2018|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Elverum would go on to denounce the title, calling it absurd and that he sought out to inject beauty into the record.<ref name=\"atlantic\"/>\n\nSome reviewers said that it was difficult to review the album. In his positive review for ''[[Drowned in Sound]]'', JR Moores did not give the album a score because \"even awarding this work the full ten-out-of-ten would feel too callous given the tragic circumstances of the record's gestation and its heartbreaking subject matter.\"<ref name=\"dis\">{{cite web |last1=Moores |first1=JR |title=Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked at Me |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/19863/reviews/4150889 |website=[[Drowned in Sound]] |accessdate=November 18, 2018 |date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> Reviewer Matthew Smith of ''No Ripcord'' said that \"assigning a score to a project like this is reductive...it's almost insulting to rank something as open and raw as this.\"<ref name=\"noripcord\">{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Matthew |title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me |url=http://www.noripcord.com/reviews/music/mount-eerie/crow-looked-me |website=No Ripcord |accessdate=December 5, 2018 |date=March 23, 2017}}</ref> ''PopMatters'' reviewer Thomas Britt called the album a \"masterpiece\" but noted that it went beyond \"the limits of conventional music criticism.\"<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> Marvin Lin from ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]'' did score the album but said that his rating meant \"absolutely nothing\".<ref name=\"tmt\"/> Lucas Koprowski from ''[[Atwood Magazine]]'' wrote that \"Breaking down any of these tracks for you would not only disrespect the meaning behind this album, but force you to swallow my interpretation of his words into a silence that is bottomless and real.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://atwoodmagazine.com/crow-looked-me-mount-eerie-review/|title=Our Take: Mount Eerie Transmit Devastation With 'A Crow Looked At Me'|publisher=[[Atwood Magazine]]|last=Koprowski|first=Lucas|date=June 2, 2017|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> While reviewing a live performance of the album Jochan Embley of ''The Independent'' commented that it \"feels weird giving a star rating to another human's honest and unshrinking account of loss\".<ref name=\"Independent Tour\"/>\n\n===Accolades===\n''A Crow Looked at Me'' appeared on numerous year-end top lists.<ref name=\"Mc3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-released-in-2017|title=The Best Albums Of 2017|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Such as ''The Atlantic'',<ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/> ''Consequence of Sound'',<ref name=\"COS\"/> ''Earbuddy'',<ref name=\"Earbuddy\"/> ''Exclaim!'',<ref name=\"Exclaim\"/> ''Paste'',<ref name=\"paste_best\"/> and ''Tiny Mix Tapes''.<ref name=\"TMT 2\"/> The lead single \"Real Death\" was third on ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s list of 100 \"Best Songs\" of 2017.<ref name=\"Pitchfork Best\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-100-best-songs-of-2017/?page=9|title=The 100 Best Songs of 2017|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> Metacritic, which collates reviews of music albums, named it the second best-reviewed album of 2017<ref name=\"Mc3\"/> and the seventh best reviewed album of decade.<ref name=\"Mc2\" />{{efn|Its appearance on the list made it the highest rated [[Contemporary Folk Music|folk]] album of the decade.<ref name=\"Mc2\" />}} According to [[Acclaimed Music]], the album is eleventh most critically album of 2017, eightieth of the 2010s and eight hundred twenty-sixth of all time.<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A5951.htm|title=Mount Eerie A Crow Looked at Me|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>{{efn|The tenth-highest ranking for an [[indie folk]] album.<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/genre/genre261.htm|title=Top Indie Folk Albums|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>}} The album is the eleventh highest rated album on [[AnyDecentMusic?]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/chart/AllTime.aspx|title=All Time Chart|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In 2020 music review site ''Treblezine'' listed as one the of \"10 Essential Home-Recorded Albums\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.treblezine.com/10-essential-home-recorded-albums/|title=10 Essential Home-Recorded Albums|website=Treblezine|last=Nierenberg|first=Jacob|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+Year-end lists\n|-\n! Publication\n! Accolade\n! Rank\n|-\n|''[[The Atlantic]]''\n| The 10 Best Albums of 2017\n| 6<ref name=\"atlanticbest\">{{cite web |last1=Kornhaber |first1=Spencer |title=The 10 Best Albums of 2017 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/12/best-albums-2017/547451/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]''\n| Clash Albums Of The Year 2017\n| 54<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/clash-albums-of-the-year-2017|title=Clash Albums Of The Year 2017|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|last1=Clash Staff|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| Top 50 Albums of 2017\n| 8<ref name=\"COS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/12/top-50-albums-of-2017/5/|title=Top 50 Albums of 2017|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last1=Cos Staff|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Earbuddy''\n| Earbuddy's 100 Best Albums of 2017\n| 1<ref name=\"Earbuddy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.earbuddy.net/70003/earbuddys-100-best-albums-of-2017.html/albums-of-the-year|title=Earbuddy's 100 Best Albums of 2017|website=Earbuddy|last=Krenn|first=Nick|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| Top 10 Folk and Country Albums of 2017\n| 2<ref name=\"Exclaim\">{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/exclaim_s_top_10_folk_and_country_albums-best_of_2017/page/2|title=Top 10 Folk and Country Albums of 2017|last=Staff|first=Exclaim!|work=Exclaim!|date=December 4, 2017|accessdate=Jan 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 14<ref name=\"fact_best\">{{cite web |last1=Horner |first1=Al |title=The 50 best albums of 2017 |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/12/20/best-albums-2017/ |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Guardian]]''\n| The Best Albums Of 2017\n| 47<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/05/the-best-albums-of-2017|last1=Guardian staff|title=The Best Albums Of 2017|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 5, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 9<ref name=\"paste_best\">{{cite web |last1=Paste staff |title=The 50 Best Albums of 2017 |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/11/the-50-best-albums-of-2017.html?p=5 |website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=November 27, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Pigeons & Planes]]''\n| Best Albums of 2017\n| 32<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2017/12/best-albums-of-2017-end-of-year/mount-eerie-crow-looked-at-me||title=Best Albums of 2017|website=[[Pigeons & Planes]]|last=Price|first=Joe|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Popmatters]]''\n| The 60 Best Albums of 2016\n| 24<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/60-best-albums-of-2017-2516162820.html|title=The 60 Best Albums of 2016|website=[[Popmatters]]|last=Britt|first=Thomas|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 14<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-50-best-albums-of-2017/?page=4|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2017|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|author=Pitchfork Staff|date=December 12, 2017|accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Noisey]]''\n| The 100 Best Albums of 2017\n| 23<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/pazbwn/noisey-100-best-albums-of-2017|title=The 100 Best Albums of 2017|website=[[Noisey]]|last=Joyce|first=Joyce|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''No Ripcord''\n| The Best Albums Of 2017\n| 11<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noripcord.com/features/best-albums-2017|title=The Best Albums Of 2017|website=No Ripcord|last=Coleman|first=David|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[NPR]]\n| The 50 Best Albums Of 2017\n| 31<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/12/12/568400855/the-50-best-albums-of-2017|title=The 50 Best Albums Of 2017|publisher=[[NPR]]|last1=NPR Staff|date=December 12, 2017|accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Spectrum Culture]]''\n| Top 20 Albums of 2017\n| 12<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spectrumculture.com/2017/12/19/top-20-albums-2017/2/|title=Top 20 Albums of 2017|website=[[Spectrum Culture]]|last1=Spectrum Culture Staff|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| 50 Best Album of 2016\n| 23<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/featured/50-best-albums-2017/|title=50 Best Album of 2016|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|last=Berman|first=Judy|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Sputnikmusic]]''\n| Staff's Top 50 Albums of 2017\n| 14<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/blog/2017/12/21/staffs-top-50-albums-of-2017-30-11/|title=Staff's Top 50 Albums of 2017: 30 \u2013 11|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|last=Robertson|first=Alex|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Stereogum]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/featured/the-50-best-albums-of-2017/|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2017|author=''Stereogum'' Staff|work=[[Stereogum]]|date=December 5, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]''\n| 2017: Favorite 50 Music Releases\n| 1<ref name=\"TMT 2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/features/2017-favorite-50-music-releases?page=4|title=2017: Favorite 50 Music Releases|last1=TMT Staff|work=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|date= December 18, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]''\n| Under the Radar's Top 100 Albums of 2017\n| 19<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.undertheradarmag.com/lists/under_the_radar_top_100_albums_of_2017/|title=Under the Radar's Top 100 Albums of 2017|website=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]|last=Wyatt|first=Stephen|date=December 30, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| The Top 100 Albums of 2017\n| 15<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/22/pazz-jop-the-top-albums-and-singles-of-2017/|title=Pazz & Jop: It's Kendrick's and Cardi's World. We're All Just Living in It|website=[[The Village Voice]]|last1=The Editors|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+Decade-end lists\n|-\n! Publication\n! List\n! Rank\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| ''All Things Loud''\n| All Things Loud's Album Of The Decade\n|{{center|18}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allthingsloud.com/things-louds-album-decade-top-20/|title=All Things Loud's Album Of The Decade:The Top 20|website=All Things Loud|last=Parker|first=Jack|date=December 5, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[University of Idaho #Library|The Argonaut]]''\n| Looking Back and Determining The Best Albums of the Decade\n|{{center|3}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"Idaho\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uiargonaut.com/2019/12/03/looking-back-and-determining-the-best-albums-of-the-decade/|title=Looking Back and Determining The Best Albums of the Decade|publisher=[[University of Idaho #Library|The Argonaut]]|last=Kowatsch|first=Teren|date=December 3, 2019|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''Consequence Of Sound''\n| Top 100 Albums of the 2010s\n|{{center|54}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/12/top-albums-of-the-2010s/6/|title=Top 100 Albums of the 2010s|website=[[Consequence Of Sound]]|last=Melis|first=Matt|date=December 30, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''Pitchfork''\n| The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s\n|{{center|45}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"pitchfork2\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-200-best-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 8, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[Portland Mercury]]''\n| The Top 5 Albums of the 2010s (According to Mercury Editorial Staff)\n|{{center|N/A{{efn|Albums aren't ranked in a chronological numbered order.}}}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"pm2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/music/2019/12/19/27664069/the-top-5-albums-of-the-2010s-according-to-mercury-editorial-staff|title=The Top 5 Albums of the 2010s (According to Mercury Editorial Staff)|publisher=[[Portland Mercury]]|last=Terwillger|first=Chipp|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''Noisey''\n| The 100 Best Albums of the 2010s\n|{{center|17}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"Vice2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/qvg5j3/the-100-best-albums-of-the-2010s|title=The 100 Best Albums of the 2010s|website=[[Noisey]]|last=Joyce|first=Colin|date=November 6, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''Melisma Magazine''\n| Our Favourite Albums of the 2010s\n|{{center|N/A{{efn|Albums aren't ranked in a chronological numbered order.}}}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"MM>{{cite web|url=https://melismamagazine.com/2019/12/29/our-favorite-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=Our Favourite Albums of the 2010s|publisher=Melisma Magazine|last=Norton|first=Mike|date=December 29, 2019|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''Metacritic''\n| The Best Albums of the Decade (2010\u20132019)\n|{{center|7}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"Mc2\">{{cite web |last1=Dietz |first1=Jason |title=The Best Albums of the Decade (2010\u201319) |url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-of-the-decade-2010s |publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020 |date=November 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115223758/https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-of-the-decade-2010s |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n|- \n| ''Tiny Mix Tapes''\n| 2010s: Favorite 100 Music Releases of the Decade\n|{{center|22}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/features/2010s-favorite-100-music-releases-decade?page=3|title=2010s: Favorite 100 Music Releases of the Decade|last1=TMT Staff|work=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks are written and produced by Phil Elverum.<ref name=\"dis\"/><ref name=\"wync\">{{cite podcast|host=Tom Power|title=July 4: How music helped Phil Elverum grieve his wife's death|website=WNYC|date=July 4, 2017|time=10:00-10:12|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/july-4-how-music-helped-phil-elverum-grieve-his-wifes-death/|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 41:30\n| title1 = Real Death\n| length1 = 2:27\n| title2 = Seaweed\n| length2 = 3:01\n| title3 = Ravens\n| length3 = 6:39\n| title4 = Forest Fire\n| length4 = 4:15\n| title5 = Swims\n| length5 = 4:07\n| title6 = My Chasm\n| length6 = 2:22\n| title7 = When I Take Out the Garbage at Night\n| length7 = 2:25\n| title8 = Emptiness pt. 2\n| length8 = 3:28\n| title9 = Toothbrush/Trash\n| length9 = 3:52\n| title10 = Soria Moria\n| length10 = 6:33\n| title11 = Crow\n| length11 = 2:21\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the album's liner notes and Cult MLT.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|others=Phil Elverum|title=A Crow Looked at Me|year=2017|publisher=[[Phil Elverum #Career|P. W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd]]}}</ref><ref name=\"cult\"/>\n*Phil Elverum{{spaced en dash}} songwriting{{spaced en dash}} vocals{{spaced en dash}} production{{spaced en dash}}  acoustic guitar{{spaced en dash}} electric guitar{{spaced en dash}} drum machine{{spaced en dash}} bass{{spaced en dash}} piano{{spaced en dash}} accordion\n\n==Release history==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Region\n! Label\n! Format\n! Category\n! Reference\n|-\n| United States\n| P. W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.\n| [[Phonograph record|Double LP]], [[Digital distribution|Digital Download]]\n| ELV040\n|<ref name=\"pwelverumandsun\">{{cite web|title=A Crow Looked At Me by Mount Eerie|url=http://www.pwelverumandsun.com/store#mounteerie|website=P.W. Elverum And Sun|accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Japan\n| P. W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.\n| [[CD]]\n| EPCD101\n|<ref name=\"pwelverumandsun\"/>\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|1154519|A Crow Looked at Me}}\n\n{{Mount Eerie}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crow Looked at Me}}\n[[Category:2017 albums]]\n[[Category:Mount Eerie albums]]\n[[Category:P. W. Elverum & Sun albums]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n[[Category:Works about cancer]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|8th Mount Eerie album}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Crow Looked at Me\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Mount Eerie]]\n| cover      = Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked at Me.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        = Male hand holding the [[Joanne Kyger]] poem \"Night Palace\" in the foreground. Background is of a house illuminated by an orange light\n| released   = {{startdate|2017|3|24}}\n| recorded   = August 31&nbsp;\u2013 December 6, 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Home recording]], [[Anacortes, Washington]]\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Indie folk]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=41|s=30}}\n| label      = P.W. Elverum & Sun\n| producer   = [[Phil Elverum]]\n| prev_title = [[Sauna (Mount Eerie album)|Sauna]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Now Only]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = A Crow Looked at Me\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Real Death\n | single1date = January 18, 2017\n | single2     = Ravens\n | single2date = February 15, 2017\n}}\n}}\n'''''A Crow Looked at Me''''' is the eighth studio album by [[Mount Eerie]], the solo project of American musician [[Phil Elverum]], released on March 24 2017 on Elverum's own label, P.W. Elverum & Sun. It is a [[concept album]] about the death of Elverum's wife, the Canadian cartoonist and musician [[Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e]]. The album was written and produced entirely by Elverum, who recorded it using mostly Castr\u00e9e's instruments in the room in which she died. A departure from Elverum's previous work, ''A Crow Looked at Me'' features minimal production and sparse instrumentation alongside lyrics that tell of Castr\u00e9e's illness and death, and Elverum's ensuing grief.\n\nPrior to the release of the album, Elverum released two singles, \"Real Death\" and \"Ravens\", released on January 18, 2017, and February 15, 2017, respectively. ''A Crow Looked at Me'' was an immediate and widespread critical success, appearing on numerous year-end lists. In the years following its release, the album has appeared in multiple decade-end lists. Some critics found that due to the album's personal nature, reviewing it felt difficult and disrespectful.\n\n==Background and composition==\n[[File:Gary Snyder, Mark Kozelek, Julie Doiron, Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd.jpg|thumb|left|250x250px|From left to right: Poet Gary Snyder, American musician Mark Kozelek, Norwegian writter Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd and Canadian singer-songwriter Julie Doiron, all of which Phil Elverum took inspiration from]]\n\nIn 2015, [[Phil Elverum]]'s wife, Canadian cartoonist and musician [[Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e]], was diagnosed with [[pancreatic cancer]] four months after the birth of their first child. Castr\u00e9e died at their home on July 9, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoo|first1=Noah|title=Genevi\u00e8ve Elverum Has Died|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/66697-genevieve-elverum-has-died|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=July 10, 2016|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Taking inspiration from the [[Gary Snyder]] poem \"Go Now\",<ref name=\"exclaim_gormely\">{{cite web |last1=Gormely |first1=Ian |title=Microphones, Mount Eerie and Melancholy: The Career of Phil Elverum |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/microphones_mount_eerie_and_melancholy_the_career_of_phil_elverum |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate= November 16, 2018 |date=November 5, 2018}}</ref> Elverum realised that he did not have to find any meaning in Castr\u00e9e's death but could write songs that described the experience.<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite web |last1=Kornhaber |first1=Spencer |title=The Pointlessness and Promise of Art After Death |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/03/mount-eerie-now-only-interview-phil-elverum/555485/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> He also found inspiration in the work of Canadian singer-songwriter [[Julie Doiron]], American singer-songwriter [[Will Oldham]], American rock band [[Sun Kil Moon]] and Norwegian author [[Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd]].<ref name=\"pearce\">{{cite web |last1=Pearce |first1=Sheldon |title=Mount Eerie Announces New Album, Shares New Song 'Real Death' |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/70642-mount-eerie-announces-new-album-shares-new-song-real-death-listen/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 21, 2018 |date=January 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"self-titled\">{{cite web|url=http://www.self-titledmag.com/new-mount-eerie-album-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie Reveals Deeply Personal Album, A Crow Looked At Me|magazine=Self-Titled|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Elverum felt compelled to make the album as he found that the art he used to treasured was ineffective at helping him cope, saying to Donovan Burtan of ''[[Cult MTL]]'' that \"all the things that used to bring me a sense of meaning and depth and comfort, all these books in the house of poetry, philosophy and everything \u2014 all of it was just empty and useless\".<ref name=\"cult\"/> \n\n{{Quote box \n|width=270px\n|align=right\n|title=\n|author=\n|salign=right\n|bgcolor=#f6f7f0\n|tstyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:100%;\n|quote =\"Songs in the future. No reverb. Close and direct. Dense with easy words. Don\u2019t rely on hanging emotions or drawn-out notes. Engage the mind\u2019s chewing teeth. Say everything as it is. No metaphors. Resist big-picture reflections.\" An example of the notes which Elverum wrote.<ref name=\"Stosuy\" />}}\n\nAfter Castree's death, Elverum considered retiring from music as a whole and becoming a full time father but a trip to [[Haida Gwaii]] inspired \nhim to write notes which would become the album (alongside the notes that he had written during Castr\u00e9e's illness and treatment).<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/><ref>{{Cite podcast|host=Jesse Thorn|title=Werner Herzog and Mount Eerie\u2019s Phil Elverum|website=Maxiumin Fun|publisher=Bullseye with Jesse Thorn|date=April 24, 2017|time=24:37-25:20|url=https://maximumfun.org/episodes/bullseye-with-jesse-thorn/bullseye-jesse-thorn-werner-herzog-and-phil-elverum/|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> Elverum recorded the album from August 31, 2016 to December 6 of the same year at his house in [[Anacortes, Washington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.folkradio.co.uk/2017/01/mount-eerie-real-death/|title=Mount Eerie Shares Song From New Album: Real Death|website=Folk Radio|last=Gallacher|first=Alex|date=January 26, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"now\"/> He wrote the songs over a six-week period<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> starting in September 2016.<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\">{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Jayson |title=Death Is Real: Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Copes With Unspeakable Tragedy |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/profile/10034-death-is-real-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-copes-with-unspeakable-tragedy/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 13, 2017}}</ref> He wrote the lyrics down longhand on her notepaper<ref name=\"tmt\">{{cite web |last1=Lin |first1=Marvin |title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked At Me |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/mount-eerie-crow-looked-me |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]| date=2017 |accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> and recorded the songs in the room where she died using an acoustic guitar, one microphone and a laptop computer<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> alongside some of Castr\u00e9e's own instruments.<ref name=\"cos\"/> Since he had become the primary carer for his daughter, Elverum recorded the songs at night while his daughter was asleep{{efn|Elverum recorded some of the songs with her sleeping 10 feet away.<ref name=\"LARB\"/>}} or during times when she was visiting friends.<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> In a interview Elverum talked about how he would choose recording over self care: \"I can either have a shower for the first time in, like, two weeks or I can write down these ideas that have been bursting in my head.\"<ref name=\"lie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.liveineverett.com/blog//an-interview-with-phil-elverum-of-mount-eeriethe-microphones|title=An Interview With Phil Elverum of Mount Eerie|website=Live In Everett|last1=Porter|first1=Christa|last2=Porter|first2=Richard|date=March 19, 2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nElverum stated that the songs \"poured out quickly in the fall, watching the days grey over and watching the neighbors across the alley tear down and rebuild their house\", with him filling the pages of his notebook with \"formless, no-rhythm, no-meter, no-melody blob of words\".<ref name=\"abc\"/><ref name=\"fact_announce\"/> Elverum said he made and released the record in order to \"multiply my voice saying that I love her. I want it known.\" and draw a distinction between \"art and music versus the actual experience of life\".<ref name=\"fact_announce\">{{cite web |last1=Bowe |first1=Miles |title=Mount Eerie addresses his wife's death on new album A Crow Looked At Me |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/01/25/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-crow-looked-at-me-real-death/ |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=January 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cult\"/> When writing the album Elverum intended for the songs to have a \"sort of hyper-intimate, no restraint\" quality to them and to be more philosophical in nature<ref name=\"observer\"/> but devoid of symbolism and distinct from the more existential themes of his earlier work.<ref>{{Cite podcast|host=Jesse Thorn|title=Werner Herzog and Mount Eerie\u2019s Phil Elverum|website=Maxiumin Fun|publisher=Bullseye with Jesse Thorn|date=April 24, 2017|time=29:30-30:30|url=https://maximumfun.org/episodes/bullseye-with-jesse-thorn/bullseye-jesse-thorn-werner-herzog-and-phil-elverum/|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Concordian\">{{cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2017/09/how-mount-eerie-copes-with-personal-grief/|title=How Mount Eerie copes with personal grief|publisher=[[The Concordian (Montreal)|The Concordian]]|last=Walker|first=Erin|date=September 12, 2017|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> Elverum revealed in an interview that he did not have a goal in mind while creating the album, saying instead that he was in an \"unpremeditated way going with the flow\".<ref name=\"cult\">{{cite web|url=https://cultmtl.com/2017/09/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-interview/|title=Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum on music and grief|website=[[Cult MTL]]|last=Burtan|first=Donovan|date=September 12, 2017|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He has also stated that he doesn't view the album as tribute or even being about Castr\u00e9e believing if he were to make a tribute it would be ineffective at capturing who Castr\u00e9e was, instead viewing the album as a documentation of his grief and of him \"saying all the heavy stuff with no regard for other people\u2019s sensitivity or unwillingness\", detached from Castr\u00e9e.<ref name=\"cult\"/><ref name=\"abc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/doublej/music-reads/features/mount-eerie-is-not-just-poking-at-sadness/10266514|title=Mount Eerie is not just poking at sadness|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]|date=January 23, 2018|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LARB\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.lareviewofbooks.org/interviews/un-treasured-time-conversation-phil-elverum/|title=Un-treasured Time: A Conversation with Phil Elverum|publisher=[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]|last=Marrs|first=Cypress|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Elverum found the recording process as a positive, calling it \"therapeutic\" and saying it felt as if he was \"hanging out with her [Castr\u00e9e]\" and feeling by the end as if he had healed.<ref name=\"Mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2997421/phil-elverum-mount-eerie-interview/|title=Phil Elverum On Life, Death And Meaninglessness|publisher=[[MTV]]|last=Garvey|first=Meghan|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"kexp\">{{cite web|url=https://kexp.org/read/2020/2/13/music-heals-phil-elverum-expressing-grief-through-music-and-remembering-his-late-wife-genevieve-castree/|title=Music Heals: Phil Elverum on Expressing Grief Through Music and Remembering His Late Wife Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e|website=Kexp|last=Fox|first=Emily|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe cover of the album features a photograph of the [[Joanne Kyger]]{{efn|Kyger died of lung cancer two days before the album's release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Joanne-Kyger-trailblazing-Beat-poet-dies-at-82-11021799.php|title=Joanne Kyger, trailblazing Beat poet, dies at 82|author=John McMurtie|accessdate=March 25, 2017|date=March 23, 2017|publisher=[[San Francisco Gate]]}}</ref>}} poem \"Night Palace\", which Castr\u00e9e had pinned above her desk.<ref name=\"observer\">{{cite web |last1=Joffe |first1=Justin |title=Beyond Grief: How Mount Eerie Made an Album About His Wife's Death |url=https://observer.com/2017/03/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-interview/ |website=[[observer.com|Observer]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> Elverum had taken the photograph while he was cleaning out her room after she died and realised that the poem encapsulated the theme of the album. Castr\u00e9e's copy of [[Herg\u00e9]]'s ''[[Tintin in Tibet]]'' can be seen in the background.<ref name=\"bandcamp\">{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Erin Lyndal |title=Mount Eerie on Intimate Grief and the Creative Impulse |url=https://daily.bandcamp.com/2017/03/21/mount-eerie-interview/ |publisher=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=November 29, 2018|date=March 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n[[File:Mount_Eerie,_Real_Death.ogg|thumb|260x300px|right|The album opener introduces the theme that \"death is real\" which Elverum once said \"could be the name\" of the album.<ref name=\"fact_announce\" />]]\n\nThe lyrics are delivered in a [[Sprechgesang|speak-singing]], conversational manner<ref name=\"SC\"/> and deal with Castr\u00e9e's illness and death, and Elverum's ensuing grief, which is the thematic concept of the album along with the theme of there being nothing to learn or gain from death.<ref name=\"exclaim_after\">{{cite web |last1=Gormely |first1=Ian |title=Phil Elverum Reveals How Mount Eerie Live Album '(After)' Puts Mourning to Rest |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/phil_elverum_reveals_how_mount_eerie_live_album_after_puts_mourning_to_rest |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=September 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|last1=Gotrich|first1=Lars|title=Stream Mount Eerie's Heartbreaking New Album, 'A Crow Looked At Me'|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/03/16/520013269/first-listen-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me |publisher=[[NPR]]|date=March 16, 2017|accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"arena\">{{cite web|url=https://arena.com/article/a-crow-looked-at-me-mount-eerie|title=A Crow Looked At Me: Death and Nature on New Mount Eerie Album|website=Arena|last=Sanna|first=Jacopo|date=March 30, 2017|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Elverum's vocals have been described as \"weak and shy\" which \"show us an artist that is completely consumed by a cruel, unforgiving world\".<ref name=\"bch\"/> The words take the form of a diary with Elverum intending for each song to reflect a time in his grieving, and include references to specific events and dates throughout. Elverum said that \"each song is anchored to a very specific moment\".<ref name=\"Stosuy\" /> Writer Thomas Britt wrote that this showcases \"the way that death hangs over each day that follows\".<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> Each song refers to Castr\u00e9e, sometimes directly by name, Elverum frequently uses pronouns such as \"our\" when referring to Castr\u00e9e despite her absence, one critic noted that this is because Elverum \"struggles to adjust to the undesired change\".<ref name=\"tmt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> The final song \"Crow\" is however addressed prominently to their daughter.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |last1=Caramanica |first1=Jon |title=The Sound of Sadness Overwhelms and Inspires Mount Eerie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/22/arts/music/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate= November 28, 2018 |date=March 22, 2017}}</ref> The lyrics have been described to \"combine emotional intimacy and tonal frankness to a degree rarely heard in contemporary music\" and as \"unspooling pieces of prose\"<ref name=\"New Yorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/in-a-room-listening-to-phil-elverum-sing-about-his-wifes-death|title=In A Room Listening To Phil Elverum Sing About His Wife's Death|website=[[The New Yorker]]|last=Baker|first=Peter C|date=September 6, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/nov/14/mount-eerie-review-phil-elverum|title=Mount Eerie review \u2013 truth defeats beauty on stark songs of death|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Hann|first=Michael|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The songwriting has been described as \"brilliant examples of breaking the fourth wall\" and that the term itself does not align with the style of the material claiming it's \"too precise\", noting the blurred lines \"between singing, speaking and raw emotional data dump.\"<ref name=\"berkle\">{{cite web|url=https://online.berklee.edu/takenote/mount-eerie-expressing-emptiness-in-songwriting/|title=Death is Real: Mount Eerie and the Art of Expressing 'Emptiness' through Songwriting|publisher=[[Berklee]]|last=Zavada|first=Eric|date=2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt\"/>\n\nOpening track \"Real Death\" features spoken-word vocals which are \"whispered from a void of hurt\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.treblezine.com/34446-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review/|title=Mount Eerie A Crow Looked At Me Review|website=Treblezine|last=Roesler|first=Brian|date=2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The song concerns itself with the \"impossibility of representing loss\", \"the hopelessness that comes after the death\" and \"highlights the inherent permanence of death with strikingly plain descriptions of the last few days and weeks of Castr\u00e9e\u2019s life\".<ref name=\"Kurki\">{{cite journal|last=Hilla|first=Kurki|date=2018|title=Notes on loss and photography|url=https://aaltodoc.aalto.fi/handle/123456789/31397|publisher=[[Aalto University]]|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"the cowl\"/><ref name=\"bch\">{{cite web|url=https://bcheights.com/2017/04/05/emotions-fly-crow-looked/|title=Emotions Fly in \u2018A Crow Looked At Me\u2019|website=The Heights|last=Guarna|first=Tomas|date=April 5, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> The song features the opening lyrics, \"death is real\" with the theme continuing throughout the record (along with the phrase itself).<ref name=\"wuog\">{{cite web|url=http://wuog.org/index.php/2017/04/04/featured-review-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked at Me|website=WUOG|last=Elder|first=Drew|date=April 4, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"allmusic\"/><ref name=\"nyt\"/> The song also introduces the theme of the album not being an artistic statement, with Phillip Green of Cisternyard Media speculating the reason behinds Elverum's aversion is that to do so \"would be taking advantage of Genevieve's passing\".<ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> The song also refers to Elverum opening mail packages addressed to Castr\u00e9e that were delivered after her death, with one critic saying that the moment \"limns the space between the living and the dead\"<ref name=\"nyt\"/> Elverum discusses scattering Castr\u00e9e's ashes and the house they intended to build on \"Seaweed\". It is composed of \"warm\" guitar plucking, \"discordant\" piano and \"hollowed\" [[bass guitar|bass]].<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> The song also introduces the themes of Castr\u00e9e's \"Spiritual omnipresence\", Castree \"surviving\" through their daughter and Elverum remembering her beyond the physical, choosing to immortalize her as the sunset, instead of as ashes.{{efn|Elverum also remembers her as a foxglove in [[Haida Gwaii]] and a fly in his house.<ref name=\"arena\"/>}}<ref name=\"allmusic\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> Writer Molly Beauchemin stated that the song \"stands apart for its crushing invocation of nature as a place of solace and refuge\u2013 a place to see purpose in the midst of loss\"<ref name=\"Garden\">{{cite web|url=https://gardencollage.com/heal/mind-spirit/mount-eeries-seaweed-heartbreaking-reflection-love-death-nature/|title=Mount Eerie's 'Seaweed' Is A Heartbreaking Reflection on Love, Death, and Nature|magazine=Garden Collage|last=Beauchemin|first=Molly|date=May 28, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> \"Ravens\" describes Elverum giving away Castr\u00e9e's clothes.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> \"Ravens\" standing apart from the other songs features multiple tempo changes.{{efn|\"Soria Moria\" also features tempo changes.<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/>}}<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> It has been described as the centrepiece of the album with its \"hushed acoustic guitar, ominous piano notes, and stark reminders of Genevi\u00e8ve's absence\"<ref name=\"capc\">{{cite web|url=https://christandpopculture.com/mount-eeries-crow-looked-confronts-horror-death/|title=Mount Eerie's A Crow Looked at Me Confronts the Horror of Death|website=Christ and Pop Culture|last=Morehead|first=Jason|date=April 14, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Sam Sodomsky of [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] called the song a \"seven-minute exploration of the horrors of this world\".<ref name=\"pitchfork ravens\" /> The track \"Forest Fire\" describes Elverum's feelings of death, decay, and absurdity in relation to the world around him. As well as apologizing to Castr\u00e9e for attempting to move on. and wondering how he will live without Castr\u00e9e.<ref name=\"nyt2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/04/magazine/new-sentences-from-forest-fire-by-mount-eerie.html|title=New Sentences: From 'Forest Fire,' by Mount Eerie|website=[[The New York Times]]|last=Abebe|first=Nitsuh|date=April 4, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"No ripcord\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.noripcord.com/reviews/music/mount-eerie/crow-looked-me|title=A Crow Looked at Me|website=No Ripcord|last=Smith|first=Matthew|date=March 23, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"bch\"/> Nitsuh Abebe of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described the song as a \"perfectly accurate description of our actual world\".<ref name=\"nyt2\"/> \"Swims\" details Elverum's experiences with [[grief counselling]] and the sudden death of his counsellor in light of Castr\u00e9e's death. It was described by one reviewer as \"one of the most heart wrenching songs created\".<ref name=\"GA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.getalternative.com/review-mount-eerie-crow-looked/|title=Review: Mount Eerie \u2013 \u2018A Crow Looked At Me\u2019|website=The Alternative|last=Gonzalez|first=Sean|date=April 7, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> It features minimal guitars, simple piano chords, \"echo-laden\" bass, \"[[lo-fi music|lo-fi]] soundscapes\" and what has been described as \"Elverum's most naked vocal performance\".<ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> \n\n[[Image:Theodor Kittelsen, Soria Moria.jpg|right|thumb|260x280px|''Soria Moria'' by [[Theodor Kittelsen]] (1881) inspired the track by the same name]]\n\n\"My Chasm\" demonstrates Elverum's difficulty in talking about his loss in public and has been described as \"a tribute to their everlasting love\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"fact_announce\" /> It features electronic instrumentation with piano accompaniment.<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> Elverum's vocal performance was described as having \"identifiable pain\" which is almost palpable.<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> \"When I Take the Garbage Out At Night\" invokes mundane imagery with one writer drawing comparisons to [[Sun Kil Moon]]'s ''[[Benji (album)|Benji]]''.<ref name=\"SC\"/> \"Emptiness pt. 2\" deals with the idea of \"conceptual emptiness\" with Elverum comparing his grief to \"climbing up a mountain in complete loneliness\".<ref name=\"now\">{{cite news|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/mount-eerie-album-review/|title=Mount Eerie's A Crow Looked At Me is unsettlingly personal| newspaper=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]|last=Greene|first=Sarah|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"bch\"/> Thomas Britt of ''[[PopMatters]]'' wrote that \"This self-reflexive commentary reframes even the most powerful pictures of wind-hewn, frosted, blackened solitude in the past Microphones/Mount Eerie songbook as products of comparative comfort; luxuries of imagination\".<ref name=\"popmatters\" /> Elverum discusses the fading familiar memories of Castr\u00e9e on the song \"Toothbrush/Trash\" has been described as a \"horrible realization that time will not relent\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/> as well as the \"most uplifting track\" on the album which conveys \"the paradoxically happy and miserable state of acceptance\".<ref name=\"radio\">{{cite web|url=https://radioutd.com/blog/2017/03/mount-eerie-crow-looked/|title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked at Me|website=Radio UTD|last=Hardaway|first=Grant|date=March 26, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Its sudden sound cue of a door closing (which Elverum recorded himself) was described by Brian Roesler as \"a haunted chamber of memory and connection that now seems more real than ever\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> The track \"Soria Moria\" takes its name from a painting of the [[Soria Moria Castle|same name]] by [[Theodor Kittelsen]], incorporates elements of [[black metal]]<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> and details Elverum's relationship with Castr\u00e9e before her death as well as referencing Elverum's time in a Norwegian cabin, in which he wrote his 2008 album [[Dawn (Mount Eerie album)|''Dawn'']] as well as interpolating the lyric \"I went back to feel alone there\" from his 2001 song [[The Glow Pt. 2|\"The Moon\"]].<ref name=\"brainwashed\">{{cite web|url=https://brainwashed.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7529:phil-elverum-qdawn-winter-journalq&catid=17:books&Itemid=134|title=Phil Elverum, 'Dawn: Winter Journal'|website=Brainwash|last=Spencer|first=Matthew|date=May 2, 2009|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"npr\" /> The final song \"Crow\" is addressed to his daughter as Elverum ponders all the ways in which Castr\u00e9e lives on, such as a crow that was following them on a hike in the Pacific Northwest. It's the only song to have references to events beyond Elverum's life, as he describes the world as \"Smoldering and fascist\", comments which were inspired by the [[2016 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"Mtv\"/> The song has been described as an \"epilogue of sorts\" which \"offers a new and hopeful perspective\" and as \"One of the more poetic tracks on the album\"<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\">{{cite web|url=https://cisternyard.com/2017/03/30/24689/|title='A Crow Looked at Me' By Mount Eerie \u2013 An Album Review|website=Cistern Yard|last=Greene|first=Phillip|date=March 30, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nMany of the lyrics feature references to nature<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> with one reviewer noting that \"tragedy hasn't stopped [Elverum] from noticing the world; if anything, it seems to have pried his eyes open for good.\"<ref name=\"Powell\"/> In her review for student newspaper \"The Cowl\" Alexus Jais noted how the songs \"seem to imply that Elverum is frustrated with a common trend to romanticize death and make it seem easier and more beautiful than perhaps it really is\".<ref name=\"the cowl\">{{cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.providence.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3182&context=cowl|title=Album Review: A Crow Looked at Me|publisher=The Cowl|last=Jais|first=Alexis|date=October 5, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Musically, the album is reminiscent of his 2008 work ''[[Lost Wisdom]]''<ref name=\"now\" /> with the songs featuring sparse instrumentation and songwriting with acoustic guitar, simple percussion, no [[chorus (song)|choruses]] and \"barely any melodies\". This was a result of Elverum wishing to move away from his earlier, more \"artistically challenging\" work, which was characterised by \"harsh tones\" and \"complicated chords\".<ref name=\"abc\"/><ref name=\"portlandmercury\">{{cite web |last1=Salmon |first1=Ben |title=On A Crow Looked at Me, Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Processes the Death of His Wife |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/music/2017/04/12/18944358/on-a-crow-looked-at-me-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-processes-the-death-of-his-wife |website=[[The Portland Mercury|Portland Mercury]] |accessdate=December 18, 2018 |date=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/><ref name=\"stereogum week\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1930429/album-of-the-week-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/franchises/album-of-the-week/|title=Album Of The Week: Mount Eerie A Crow Looked At Me|website=[[Stereogum]]|last=Breihan|first=Tom|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> The sparse nature of the album lead to Elverum referring to the album as \"barely music\".<ref name=\"Powell\"/> The album is less musically dark in comparison to the rest of the [[Mount Eerie #Discography|Mount Eerie discography]].<ref name=\"arena\"/> Elverum wanted to release the album quickly, so he used minimal [[Record producer|production]].<ref name=\"beatroute\">{{cite web |title=A Crow Looked at Me Gives Mount Eerie a Worthy Eulogy |url=https://archive.beatroute.ca/2017/08/12/crow-looked-gives-mount-eerie-worthy-eulogy/ |website=Beatroute|date=August 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref> This was Elverum's first album to be entirely produced on a computer.<ref>{{cite podcast|host=Tom Power|title=July 4: How music helped Phil Elverum grieve his wife's death|website=WNYC|date=July 4, 2017|time=10:12-10:30|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/july-4-how-music-helped-phil-elverum-grieve-his-wifes-death/|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\n{{Quote box \n|width=250px\n|align=right\n|title=Night Palace\n|author=Joanne Kyger\n|salign=right\n|bgcolor=#f6f7f0\n|tstyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:100%;\n|quote =<poem>\nThe best thing about the past\nis that it's over\nwhen you die.\nyou wake up\nfrom the dream\nthat's your life.\n\nThen you grow up\nand get to be post human\nin a past that keeps happening\nahead of you\n</poem>\n}}\n\nElverum considered not releasing the album at all, or changing his band name entirely but ultimately decided to do neither.<ref name=\"Stosuy\">{{cite web |last1=Stosuy |first1=Brandon |title=Phil Elverum on creating art from grief |url=https://thecreativeindependent.com/people/phil-elverum-on-creating-art-from-grief/ |website=The Creative Independent |accessdate=December 10, 2018 |date=March 15, 2017}}</ref> He had originally planned for a small scale release of the record on his own website, but as the album took shape he felt that it was good and wanted it to reach a wider audience.<ref name=\"noisey\">{{cite web |last1=Currin |first1=Grayson |title=How Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Faced Grief on His Devastating New Album |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/wn9z54/a-conversation-with-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-on-his-devastating-new-album |website=[[Vice_(magazine)#Website|Vice]]|date=March 28, 2017 |accessdate=November 19, 2018}}</ref> Despite this he still found releasing the album and promoting it to be \"gross and weird from a lot of perspectives\".<ref name=\"Stosuy\" /> On January 5, 2017, he announced that he would go on tour, and release a new album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoo|first1=Noah|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/70707-phil-elverum-please-dont-come-to-tomorrows-mount-eerie-show/|title=Phil Elverum: 'Please Don't Come' to Tomorrow's Mount Eerie Show|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> The next day, he played his first concert since September 2014 at a record store in [[Anacortes, Washington]]. Elverum, while choosing to perform, also asked fans to stay away as the response was \"overwhelming\" and the store could only hold 50 people.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Strauss|first1=Matthew|title=Mount Eerie Performing New Music at First Show in 2 Years|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/70637-mount-eerie-performing-new-music-at-first-show-in-2-years/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=December 30, 2016|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Elverum performed the show with his eyes closed and left immediately afterwards.<ref name=\"larecord\">{{cite web |last1=Child |first1=Tom |title=Mount Eerie: Stay Sincere |url=http://larecord.com/archive/2017/04/10/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-phil-elverum-interview |website=[[L.A. Record]] |accessdate= November 21, 2018 |date=April 10, 2017}}</ref> The first single from ''A Crow Looked at Me'', \"Real Death\", was released on P.W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.'s [[SoundCloud]] page on January 18, 2017, to widespread acclaim, netting the \"Best New Track\" distinction from ''Pitchfork''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Currin|first1=Grayson|title='Real Death' by Mount Eerie Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18708-mount-eerie-real-death/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"paste single\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/mount-eerie/mount-eerie-releases-music-video-for-ravens-announ/|title=Mount Eerie Releases Devastating 'Ravens' Video, Announces West Coast Tour Dates|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Rohrback|first=Paul|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The second single, \"Ravens\", was released on February 15, 2017, alongside a music video uploaded to Mount Eerie's official [[YouTube]] account, again earning the \"Best New Track\" distinction from ''Pitchfork'', writing that \"Elverum makes no attempts to find metaphor or meaning; when he sees two ravens flying overhead, he knows it's an omen, but he can't say what for.\"<ref name=\"pitchfork ravens\">{{cite web|last1=Sodomsky|first1=Sam|title='Ravens' by Mount Eerie Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18780-mount-eerie-ravens/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"paste single\"/> Following the release of the album, Elverum embarked on a North American tour in September 2017, playing solo shows accompanied only by his acoustic guitar in intimate venues that included \"concert halls, churches, and theaters\".<ref name=\"geslani\">{{cite web |last1=Geslani |first1=Michelle |title=Mount Eerie announces North American tour dates |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/05/mount-eerie-announces-north-american-tour-dates/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=May 31, 2017}}</ref> The tour was extended to include Europe in November 2017.<ref name=\"TMTsmart\">{{cite web |last1=Smart |first1=Dan |title=Mount Eerie announces European tour dates in November |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/mount-eerie-announces-european-tour-dates-november |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=September 20, 2017}}</ref> While performing at [[Jacobikerk]] as part of [[Le Guess Who?]] festival in [[Utrecht]], a sound engineer recorded Elverum's set without his knowledge. Elverum liked the recording so much that it was subsequently released as the live album ''[[(after)]]'' in 2018.<ref name=\"pitchforkafter\">{{cite web |last=Reese |first=Nathan |title=Mount Eerie: (after) |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/mount-eerie-after/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe tour received a postive reception. Jochan Embley of ''[[The Independent]]'' awarded the show performed at [[St John on Bethnal Green]] church five stars and wrote that Elverum \"plays and sings with such softness and space that you can hear the hum of his monitors as he does so\".<ref name=\"Independent Tour\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/mount-eerie-tour-a-crow-looked-at-me-london-tour-live-review-a8054051.html|title=Mount Eerie, St John on Bethnal Green, gig review: Beautiful art inspired by tragedy|website=[[The Independent]]|last=Embley|first=Jochan|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Adam O'Sullivan of the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' described the show as \"something truly remarkable, truly honest and something that those in attendance are unlikely ever to see again\".<ref name=\"es\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/mount-eerie-a-truly-remarkable-and-honest-portrayal-of-tragedy-a3716321.html|title=Mount Eerie at St John on Bethnal Green: A truly remarkable and honest portrayal of tragedy|publisher=[[Evening Standard]]|last=O'Sullivan|first=Adam|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> Woody Delaney of ''[[Loud and Quiet]]'' praised the show performed at Left Bank, Leeds calling it an \"experience so human, it serves to remind the audience to cherish the fragility of life, and more immediately the person sat next to them\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudandquiet.com/short/sobering-appreciation-comes-mount-eeries-devastating-grief/|title=The sobering appreciation that comes from Mount Eerie\u2019s devastating grief|publisher=[[Loud and Quiet]]|last=Delaney|first=Woody|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Aaron Badgley of ''Spill Magazine'' praised the show at the Great Hall, Toronto, Canada calling it \"one of the most memorable performances\" he has seen and concluding that \"to have the opportunity to see him do this live was one of those rare instances in life when you witnessed something truly important on stage\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spillmagazine.com/spill-live-review-mount-eerie-great-hall-toronto/|title=Spill Live Review: Mount Eerie @ Great Hall Toronto|publisher=Spill Magazine|last=Badgley|first=Aaron|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Sarah Greene, of ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now Toronto]]'' echoed similar sentiments describeing the show as \"painfullly intimate\" and stating that \"In his solo performance, Phil Elverum showed that both songwriting and grieving are an ongoing process\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/concert-reviews/mount-eerie-at-the-great-hall/|title=Mount Eerie's Great Hall concert was painfully intimate|magazine=[[Now (newspaper)|Now Toronto]]|last=Greene|first=Sarah|date=September 21, 2017|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> \n\nElverum found that due to the personal nature of the songs touring was difficult, saying it felt like he was \"going out there and re-enacting a trauma and charging people money for it\" and criticising the sense of voyeurism the audience part took in.<ref name=\"abc\"/> Elverum also did several interviews{{efn|Elverum was at one point doing five interviews in one day.<ref name=\"Portland 2\"/>}} which he found to be \"mentally draining\", although he did admit that he treated them as pseudo-[[therapy]] sessions noting how they were different from a typical [[Public Relations|PR]] campaign.<ref name=\"Portland 2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/music/2017/04/12/18944358/on-a-crow-looked-at-me-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-processes-the-death-of-his-wife|title=On A Crow Looked at Me, Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Processes the Death of His Wife|website=Portland Mercury|last=Salmon|first=Ben|date=April 12, 2017|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 8.8/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/8559/Mount-Eerie-A-Crow-Looked-at-Me.aspx|title=A Crow Looked at Me by Mount Eerie reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| MC = 93/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/a-crow-looked-at-me/mount-eerie|title=Reviews and Tracks for A Crow Looked at Me by Mount Eerie|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-crow-looked-at-me-mw0003032380|title=A Crow Looked at Me \u2013 Mount Eerie|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Phares|first=Heather|date=2017|accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/live/craig-finn-mount-eerie-pallbearer-and-more-weeks-m-252416|title=Mount Eerie confronts death on its saddest album to date|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Corcoran|first=Nina|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev3score = A\u2212<ref name=\"cos\">{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/03/album-review-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Sackllah|first=David|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4score = 9/10<ref name=\"exclaimfenech\">{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/mount_eerie-a_crow_looked_at_me|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Fenech|first=Zach|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|last=Male|first=Andrew|issue=284|date=July 2017|page=91}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n| rev6score = 9.2/10<ref name=\"paste\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/03/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review.html|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked At Me Review|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Fink|first=Matt|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 9.0/10<ref name=\"Powell\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22970-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked At Me|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Powell|first=Mike|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev8Score = 10/10<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[PopMatters]]|last=Britt|first=Thomas|date=March 20, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev9score = 9/10<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|journal=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|issue=240|date=May 2017|page=35}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' ([[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Expert Witness]])\n| rev10score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/8xvyqv/expert-witness-with-robert-christgau-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me|title=Robert Christgau on Mount Eerie's 'A Crow Looked at Me,' a Brutal Listen|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=January 27, 2018|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''A Crow Looked at Me'' received widespread critical acclaim upon release. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from [[music critic]]s, the album has received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 93, indicating \"universal acclaim\", based on 18 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave ''A Crow Looked At Me'' 8.8 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"adm\"/> Elverum found the album's reception \"reaffirming\", but was frustrated by those who viewed it as a tribute to his wife and felt uneasy about the album being public at all.<ref name=\"atlantic\"/><ref name=\"cult\"/> Heather Phares from [[AllMusic]] called the album \"remarkably powerful and pure\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''{{'}}s David Sackllah said that it was \"overwhelming and humbling\" and wrote that \"A Crow Looked at Me stands as a remarkable example of the restorative power of music, an intimate display of love, daring both in concept and execution.\"<ref name=\"cos\"/> Zack Fenech from ''[[Exclaim!]]'' said that \"this record possesses immense power to make listeners reflect on their own relationships and mortality. ''A Crow Looked at Me'' is a grim memento of the grand injustice of losing those most precious to us.\"<ref name=\"exclaimfenech\"/> [[Paste (magazine)|''Paste'']]{{'}}s Matt Fink said that it was \"beautifully and simply arranged, but it is not an entertaining album to listen to in any conventional sense, nor can it be shaken off easily. It is, however, the kind of album that makes all others seem frivolous\" and that \"there is no album quite like it.\"<ref name=\"paste\"/>\n\nBen Malkin from ''GIGsoup'' described the album \"art in its most pure, human form\", a \"showcase of weakness and cruel reality, prose of lost love,\" and \"perhaps the saddest album ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gigsoupmusic.com/reviews/album-reviews/mount-eerie-crow-looked/|title=Mount Eerie 'A Crow Looked at Me'|website=Gigsoup|last=Malkin|first=Ben|date=April 3, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In his review for ''[[Spectrum Culture]]'' John Paul said that \"Heartbreaking doesn't even begin to describe ''A Crow Looked at Me''\" and described the album as \"pure grief delivered in a voice in which you can hear the weight of loss\".<ref name=\"SC\">{{Cite web|url=https://spectrumculture.com/2017/03/28/mount-eerie/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|website=[[Spectrum Culture]]|last=Paul|first=John|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Jacopo Sanna of ''Arena Music'' claimed that ''A Crow Looked at Me'' is \"probably the most important album about death and loss ever recorded\".<ref name=\"Arena2\">{{cite web|url=https://arena.com/article/mount-eerie-and-everything-that-is-left-to-remember|title=Mount Eerie Explores Everything That's Left to Remember|website=Arena Music|last=Sanna|first=Jacopo|date=March 28, 2018|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Sarah Greene, writing for ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now Toronto]]'' described ''A Crow Looked At Me'' as \"a lovingly crafted album, with gentle melodies that linger in the air, pretty, memorable guitar lines and a subtle but persistent approach to percussion\" and concluded that despite it may being an uncomfortable and harrowing listen it was also a \"tribute to an amazing 13-year love story\".<ref name=\"now\" /> Brian Roesler, from ''Treblezine'', despite enjoying the record considerably, demanded that readers \"Don't call it art. Don't call it music even. Call it a documentation of suffering and loss as an experience, and treat it as such\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/>{{efn|A sentiment echoed by Elverum himself.<ref name=\"Powell\"/>}} In a [[essay]] written for ''[[The Spinoff]]'', Murdoch Stephens compared ''A Crow Looked At Me'' to the poetry of [[Auschwitz]] survivor [[Primo Levi]] and pondered how the listener should interact with a piece of art of such a visceral nature. He called Elverum \"the saddest musician in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/music/15-01-2018/how-to-listen-to-mount-eerie-the-saddest-musician-in-the-world/|title=How to listen to Mount Eerie, the saddest musician in the world|website=[[The Spinoff]]|last=Stephens|first=Murdoch|date=January 15, 2018|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Elverum would go on to denounce the title, calling it absurd and that he sought out to inject beauty into the record.<ref name=\"atlantic\"/>\n\nSome reviewers said that it was difficult to review the album. In his positive review for ''[[Drowned in Sound]]'', JR Moores did not give the album a score because \"even awarding this work the full ten-out-of-ten would feel too callous given the tragic circumstances of the record's gestation and its heartbreaking subject matter.\"<ref name=\"dis\">{{cite web |last1=Moores |first1=JR |title=Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked at Me |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/19863/reviews/4150889 |website=[[Drowned in Sound]] |accessdate=November 18, 2018 |date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> Reviewer Matthew Smith of ''No Ripcord'' said that \"assigning a score to a project like this is reductive...it's almost insulting to rank something as open and raw as this.\"<ref name=\"noripcord\">{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Matthew |title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me |url=http://www.noripcord.com/reviews/music/mount-eerie/crow-looked-me |website=No Ripcord |accessdate=December 5, 2018 |date=March 23, 2017}}</ref> ''PopMatters'' reviewer Thomas Britt called the album a \"masterpiece\" but noted that it went beyond \"the limits of conventional music criticism.\"<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> Marvin Lin from ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]'' did score the album but said that his rating meant \"absolutely nothing\".<ref name=\"tmt\"/> Lucas Koprowski from ''[[Atwood Magazine]]'' wrote that \"Breaking down any of these tracks for you would not only disrespect the meaning behind this album, but force you to swallow my interpretation of his words into a silence that is bottomless and real.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://atwoodmagazine.com/crow-looked-me-mount-eerie-review/|title=Our Take: Mount Eerie Transmit Devastation With 'A Crow Looked At Me'|publisher=[[Atwood Magazine]]|last=Koprowski|first=Lucas|date=June 2, 2017|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> While reviewing a live performance of the album Jochan Embley of ''The Independent'' commented that it \"feels weird giving a star rating to another human's honest and unshrinking account of loss\".<ref name=\"Independent Tour\"/>\n\n===Accolades===\n''A Crow Looked at Me'' appeared on numerous year-end top lists.<ref name=\"Mc3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-released-in-2017|title=The Best Albums Of 2017|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Such as ''The Atlantic'',<ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/> ''Consequence of Sound'',<ref name=\"COS\"/> ''Earbuddy'',<ref name=\"Earbuddy\"/> ''Exclaim!'',<ref name=\"Exclaim\"/> ''Paste'',<ref name=\"paste_best\"/> and ''Tiny Mix Tapes''.<ref name=\"TMT 2\"/> The lead single \"Real Death\" was third on ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s list of 100 \"Best Songs\" of 2017.<ref name=\"Pitchfork Best\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-100-best-songs-of-2017/?page=9|title=The 100 Best Songs of 2017|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> Metacritic, which collates reviews of music albums, named it the second best-reviewed album of 2017<ref name=\"Mc3\"/> and the seventh best reviewed album of decade.<ref name=\"Mc2\" />{{efn|Its appearance on the list made it the highest rated [[Contemporary Folk Music|folk]] album of the decade.<ref name=\"Mc2\" />}} According to [[Acclaimed Music]], the album is eleventh most critically album of 2017, eightieth of the 2010s and eight hundred twenty-sixth of all time.<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A5951.htm|title=Mount Eerie A Crow Looked at Me|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>{{efn|The tenth-highest ranking for an [[indie folk]] album.<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/genre/genre261.htm|title=Top Indie Folk Albums|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>}} The album is the eleventh highest rated album on [[AnyDecentMusic?]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/chart/AllTime.aspx|title=All Time Chart|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In 2020 music review site ''Treblezine'' listed as one the of \"10 Essential Home-Recorded Albums\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.treblezine.com/10-essential-home-recorded-albums/|title=10 Essential Home-Recorded Albums|website=Treblezine|last=Nierenberg|first=Jacob|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+Year-end lists\n|-\n! Publication\n! Accolade\n! Rank\n|-\n|''[[The Atlantic]]''\n| The 10 Best Albums of 2017\n| 6<ref name=\"atlanticbest\">{{cite web |last1=Kornhaber |first1=Spencer |title=The 10 Best Albums of 2017 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/12/best-albums-2017/547451/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]''\n| Clash Albums Of The Year 2017\n| 54<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/clash-albums-of-the-year-2017|title=Clash Albums Of The Year 2017|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|last1=Clash Staff|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| Top 50 Albums of 2017\n| 8<ref name=\"COS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/12/top-50-albums-of-2017/5/|title=Top 50 Albums of 2017|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last1=Cos Staff|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Earbuddy''\n| Earbuddy's 100 Best Albums of 2017\n| 1<ref name=\"Earbuddy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.earbuddy.net/70003/earbuddys-100-best-albums-of-2017.html/albums-of-the-year|title=Earbuddy's 100 Best Albums of 2017|website=Earbuddy|last=Krenn|first=Nick|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| Top 10 Folk and Country Albums of 2017\n| 2<ref name=\"Exclaim\">{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/exclaim_s_top_10_folk_and_country_albums-best_of_2017/page/2|title=Top 10 Folk and Country Albums of 2017|last=Staff|first=Exclaim!|work=Exclaim!|date=December 4, 2017|accessdate=Jan 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 14<ref na